<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief's Report on Work of UN Governance (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today presented his report on the work of governance of
the organization, in which he stressed that good governance was an
essential building block for meeting the objectives of sustainable
development, prosperity and peace.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said that good governance comprised the
rule of law, effective state institutions, transparency and
accountability in the management of public affairs, respect for
human rights, and the meaning participation of all citizens in the
political processes of their countries and in decisions affecting
their lives.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said that the United Nations Secretariat and
United Nations programs and funds had moved to provide extensive
governance-related support to large numbers of developing
countries and to countries in Eastern Europe and the Commonwealth
of Independence States. That took the form of analytical work,
diagnostic research, needs assessment, policy advice, technical
assistance and advisory services, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said support was provided to strengthen the functioning of
specific institutions, such as judiciaries, parliaments and
electoral bodies, as well as sectorally, including public sector
financial management, privatization efforts, information
technology, civil service reforms and the empowerment of civil
society organizations.
</P>
<P>
He said that sustainable prosperity and stability could be
achieved without good governance. The United Nations development
Program (UNDP) had been increasing the funds dedicated to this
priority, he noted. It now accounts for more than one third of all
UNDP allocations.
</P>
<P>
He said that in July 1997, the UNDP convened the first ever
International Conference in Governance for Sustainable Growth and
Equity, bringing to United Nations Headquarters elected officials,
judges and community leaders from more than 100 countries. The
United Nations Children's Fund had focused increasingly on
strengthening on local capacity and promoting community
participation. The United Nations Development Fund for Women also
operated a governance program, promoting strategies for women's
empowerment and gender mainstreaming.
</P>
<P>
Annan stressed that expanding and enhancing the exchange of
knowledge and experiences among developing countries was of
growing importance. The United Nations Secretariat would
facilitate this process through its capacity as a cleaning house
for information and research on public administration, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
