<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Protest Against Bosporus Straits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus will protest against
Turkey's violation of the 1936 International Treaty of Montreux on
navigation in the Bosporus Straits, a government spokesman said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Telling a daily press briefing, Manolis Christofides was
referring to last week's incident in which Turkish authorities
stopped and searched a Cyprus-flagged vessel "Diamond H", as it
arrived to transit the Bosporus.
</P>
<P>
The vessel was reportedly bound from Ukraine to Alexandria,
Egypt, carrying a cargo of steel products.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish authorities have recently searched ships travelling
through the Bosporus Straits, suspecting they carry components of
Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles Cyprus has bought early
this year.
</P>
<P>
Another Egyptian ship was also reported to be searched last
week but nothing was found destined for Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Christofides said "we shall make representations after we hear
the legal opinion of international consultants and act
accordingly." "At this stage, we are not in a position to give
any further details about future moves," he added.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Montreux Treaty, which governs
navigation in the Straits, incorporates provisions for the rights
of the contracting parties.
</P>
<P>
Article two of the Treaty stipulates "in time of peace,
merchant vessels shall enjoy complete freedom of transit and
navigation of the Straits, by day and by night, under any flag and
with any kind of cargo, without any formalities."
</P>
<P>
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides also said last Saturday
that the Cypriot government will lodge the protest to the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman Guennadi Tarasov said last
week that the search of commercial ships passing through the
Black Sea Straits, by Turkey, violates the Montreux convention.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus' decision to purchase Russian missiles has
triggered warning from Turkey that it will launch pre-emptive
strike against Cyprus if the missiles are deployed.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and took over 37 percent of the island in the wake
of a failed coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official: China Should Use Overseas Investment Wisely (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Sun Zhenyu, Vice-Minister of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, said today that China
should properly protect its domestic market while continuing
to open up to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Sun told a forum attended by Taiwan business people, who are
here to take part in the '97 China Investment and Trade Talks,
that China will guarantee that the state-owned enterprises have a
reasonable share of the market for some important industries and
products, especially those which affect the national economy and
the people's livelihood.
</P>
<P>
Sun emphasized that to protect the domestic market is not to
protect backwardness but to guarantee the healthy, orderly and
sustained growth of the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
To raise the amount and appropriateness of the use of overseas
funds, Sun suggested that China should optimize the industrial
structure into which overseas businessmen pour in funding.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China should better guide the direction of
overseas investments, and clearly define which fields are
available for overseas funding.
</P>
<P>
The country will further encourage overseas business people to
invest in infrastructural construction, fundamental,
export-oriented and hi-tech industries in addition to farming,
animal breeding and farm produce processing industries, Sun said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the country will properly increase overseas
investment in the energy and communication sectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official: China Should Use Overseas Investment Wisely (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Meanwhile, China plans to encourage overseas businesspeople to
invest in its central and western parts which fall far
behind the coastal areas in using overseas funds, Sun noted.
</P>
<P>
Sun stressed that those areas should emphasize the need to
introduce foreign investments as a means of developing the
regional economy.
</P>
<P>
While speeding up the infrastructural construction, those areas
can give overseas businesspeople priority in investing in the
communication, energy and raw materials industries, and encourage
them to fund the technological upgrading of large state-owned
enterprises, Sun said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that some big cities in the region can experiment with
using foreign funds in banking, insurance and retailing businesses
and encouraging overseas investors to develop tourism in the
region.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Sun stressed that the legal system should be
beefed up to improve the investment environment. He said that the
country will speed up the reform in the field and improve the
service and efficiency of government departments.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China will reinforce administrative control over
foreign-funded firms in a bid to protect the country's tax sources
and the legal rights of the employees.
</P>
<P>
China has achieved remarkable progress in using overseas
investment, with more than 290,000 foreign-backed firms
established and 197.2 billion US dollars used.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
