<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Welcomes Norway's Proposal on Textiles Freeing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) welcomes the Norwegian
government's proposal to remove all the quantitative restrictions
for imports of restrained textiles and clothing products from Hong
Kong by the end of this year, an official spokesman said here
today.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman from the Hong Kong SAR government's Trade
Department said the early elimination of quantitative restrictions
by Norway ahead of the World Trade Organization (WTO) Agreement on
Textiles and Clothing (ATC) schedule is "a welcomed move," which
contributes to the goal of complete liberalization of the textiles
trade under the ATC.
</P>
<P>
"The HKSAR government fully appreciates the efforts made by
Norway towards this goal and is delighted to accept Norway's
proposal," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal recently put forward to the Hong Kong SAR
government by the Norwegian government, exports of woven trousers
(Category 2) and woven bed-linen (Category 7) from Hong Kong into
Norway will not be subject to quantitative restraint as from
January 1, 1998, and exports of woven jackets (Category 1) will
also be derestrained from one year later.
</P>
<P>
Now, all these three categories of textiles products, namely
woven jackets, woven trousers and woven bed-linen are subject to
annual quantitative limits.
</P>
<P>
The proposal by Norway is made under the ATC. Under the
document, members of the WTO are committed to liberalization
global trade in textiles in stages with the ultimate objective of
fully integration of trade in textiles into the General Agreement
on Tariffs and Trade by 2005, the spokesman noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Economy Weakening Again: Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Barclays Bank Zimbabwe Limited
has said there are signs that Zimbabwe's economy is weakening
again following strong performance in recent years.
</P>
<P>
In its latest economic bulletin released here today, the bank
said indications of a slowing economy include the worsening terms
of trade as represented by the decline in projected values of
tobacco and gold, the leading export commodities.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, manufactured exports, the third largest export
category, are having to cope with a substantially appreciated
real exchange rate," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Private sector credit growth is now negative pointing to a
decline in domestic investment levels, while there are also
predictions of a drought in the coming season, the bulletin
added.
</P>
<P>
While applauding the government for reducing the budget
deficit from an average 9.7 percent in the financial years
1992-96 to 6.7 percent in the last financial year, the bank
however, said there has been no adequate exchange rate or
monetary policy management to match the windfall.
</P>
<P>
"The latter policy shortcomings are now being left by way of
sluggish export performance, accelerated currency depreciation
and a return to dependence on foreign aid financing," the bank
said.
</P>
<P>
Barclays also warned that high nominal and real interest rates
will lead to subdued investment and output during the early
stages of the next economic reform cycle, particularly if this
coincides with drought.
</P>
<P>
The bank said Zimbabwe's efforts to bring down inflation to
seven percent by 1999 will be difficult while the local currency
unit will have to depreciate by at least 10 percent during the
next six months in order to support the export sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
