<HEADLINE> Palestinians Criticize Israel for ID Cards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian Ministry of
Jerusalem Affairs today criticized Israel for continuously
confiscating the ID cards of Palestinians living in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said in a statement that during the last two
weeks, 182 cases of ID confiscations were reported and from
January to May this year, the Israeli authorities confiscated 787
ID cards of the Palestinians living in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"This act of Israel represents a blatant attempt by the
Israeli government to coerce the Palestinian residents of
Jerusalem into forced migration," the statement pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian residents of Jerusalem are being expelled from
Jerusalem through the revocation of their residential rights and
this policy of Israel amounts to an ethnic cleaning tactic as it
solely targets the people of Arab descent despite the
U.S. pressure, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
This Israeli policy is illegal according to international law,
it noted.
</P>
<P>
Since 1976, it said, a total of 4,661 ID cards of Palestinians
living in this city have been confiscated by the Israeli
authorities.
</P>
<P>
To protest against the ID confiscations, Palestinians have set
up a camp named Steadfastnes and Solidarity on the slope of Mount
Scopes in the city. At present, it houses 40 Palestinian
families, or 200 homeless individuals whose homes have been
demolished by the Israeli authorities recently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
