<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Tobacco Sales Set to Miss Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's tobacco marketing
season comes to an end in about two weeks with sales just
slightly below the targeted 196 million kgs, an industry official
said today.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe Tobacco Association's Public Relations Director Lal
Taylor said increased tobacco sales totaling 166.6 million kg
worth over 4.5 billion Zimbabwe Dollars (about 400 million U.S.
Dollars) were traded at the country's three auction floors as of
Friday last week.
</P>
<P>
Taylor said this volume was down from last year's and the
average price as well was not as high as that for last year.
</P>
<P>
"Tobacco marketing for this season comes to an end on
September 24, about 13 more selling days, and we may miss our
latest target of 196 million kgs by probably a small margin,"
Taylor said, adding they will have to watch sales closely in case
they shoot up significantly.
</P>
<P>
Last year, on the back of a good agricultural season and high
tobacco price, 202 million kg of tobacco earned the country over
8 billion Zimbabwe Dollars (more than 720 million U.S. Dollars).
Tobacco is Zimbabwe's biggest foreign currency earner.
</P>
<P>
The drop in this year's sales had been a result of reduced
yields due to excess rains, but still if this year's target is
met, the country will earn only about 5.6 billion Zimbabwe
Dollars (some 500 million U.S. Dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
