<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Prepares Anti-Drug Common Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAHANNESBURG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Legal experts from
southern Africa will meet next month in Botswana to prepare a
draft protocol to combat drug trafficking in the region.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made today by ministers of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) in Malawi's commercial
capital, Blantyre, venue of this year's summit of SADC leaders
which opened today.
</P>
<P>
SADC drug control advisor Bjorn Franzen was quoted by local
press as saying that there is urgent need for governments in the
region to ratify a convention to curb drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
He said narcotic abuse is on the rise throughout southern
Africa and unless urgent action is taken the menace can lead to
social and political upheaval in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Botswana meeting will draft a protocol which will provide
the legal framework for setting up laws to curb illicit drug use
and trafficking across the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
SADC was set up in 1992 and aims to create a common market in
southern Africa by the turn of the century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
