<HEADLINE> France Privatizes 20 Percent of France Telecom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The French government will sell
20 percent of the stocks of the state-owned France Telecom
telecommunication monopoly, announced French Minister of Finance
and Economy Dominique Strauss-Kahn today.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government will begin the procedure of opening
20 percent of the France Telecom stocks to public and investors on
September 22 and expects its stocks to be issued in stock markets
by October 20.
</P>
<P>
The value of the stocks of the multi-billion franc France
Telecom will be decided by October 6, said Strauss-Kahn.
</P>
<P>
The German telecommunication group, Deutsche Telekom, will buy
an extra 7 to 8 percent of the stocks of France Telecom under an
agreement of exchange with the French government, while 3 to 4
percent more stocks of the company will be bought by its
employees.
</P>
<P>
The French state will keep around 63 percent of the stocks of
France Telecom.
</P>
<P>
The French government is also considering to sell part of the
stocks of the Air France air company, but has decided to maintain
the majority of the stocks in the hands of the state.
</P>
<P>
The refusal to privatize Air France has resulted in the
resignation of its president, Christian Blanc, who proposed
privatizing the French national carrier to keep it competitive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
