<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Promises Israel to Fight Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat today promised Israel a
crackdown on terrorism to rescue the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the promise in a message conveyed by senior
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat to Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy, saying that he would fight violence in any forms.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader also thanked Levy for telling the
weekly Israeli Cabinet meeting held on Sunday that Israel
should continue to honor the Oslo agreements so to push
forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's pledge came despite Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu's criticism against him early today that he should be
indirectly responsible for the recent suicide bombings in central
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"I am not saying that Arafat told them (terrorists) to go
ahead and strike. I am saying that he facilitated the operations
within the territories. He has effectively turned the
Palestinian-controlled areas into safe heavens and bases of the
terrorist organizations," Netanyahu told Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that Arafat, during a recent national unity
conference, hugged and kissed leaders from the militant
organizations, such as the Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas)
and the Islamic Jihad.
</P>
<P>
Hamas has claimed responsibility for both the July 30 twin
suicide bombings in Jerusalem's Mahane Yehuda market that killed
17 people and last Thursday's triple suicide bombings in Ben
Yehuda pedestrian mall that killed eight people so far.
</P>
<P>
Israel reacted swiftly and strongly to the latest bombings by
immediately imposing a total blockade of the Palestinian
territories, including an internal travel ban on Palestinian
residents in the West Bank, and even freezing further troop
redeployments.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli sanctions are apparently aimed at pressuring the
PNA to launch an all-out crackdown on the militant Islamic
organizations led by Hamas.
</P>
<P>
In a gesture made ahead of the September 10 visit to the region
by United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
Palestinian security forces arrested 35 Islamic militant
activists in an overnight crackdown in the West Bank. The PNA is
apparently trying to show to the Americans that it does make real
efforts to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the deterioration of the security situation in
Israel has sparked hectic debates throughout Israeli's political
spectrum, with lawmakers from the ruling coalition and the
opposition camp trading accusations over the responsibility for
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Nissan Slomoanski, lawmaker from the National Religious Party
(NRP), a coalition party, blamed the opposition Labor party for
the crisis. He said Arafat has never acted to fight terrorism, and
the former Labor government's leaders should be put on trial by
putting the nation under the risks of terror attacks encouraged by
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Slomoanski's charges drew fierce criticism from lawmakers from
the Labor and Meretz parties who demanded the attorney-general to
indict him for inciting violence against them.
</P>
<P>
Meretz leader Yossi Sarid urged Netanyahu to resign
immediately for failing to deliver his elections promises on
bringing about peace with security to the country.
</P>
<P>
Orren Shahor, former Coordinator of Government Activities in
the Territories who has just joined the Labor party, blasted the
Netanyahu administration for trying to abandon the Oslo peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Shahor expressed the concern that the end of the Oslo peace
process would push the region back into the abyss of bloody
confrontations and wars, not only with the Palestinians, but also
with Egypt and Jordan, with which Israel has maintained peace so
far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
