<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Banks Hold Holocaust Survivors' Savings: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- British banks hold millions of
pounds belonging to holocaust survivors or their heirs, according
to a report by the Holocaust Educational Trust (HET).
</P>
<P>
The report, published today, said that the British government
did not return all the assets confiscated during World War II from
thousands of Nazi victims.
</P>
<P>
HET Chairman Lord Janner was quoted by today's Financial Times
as saying, "I have asked the government and the banks to make full
restitution so far as it is possible."
</P>
<P>
The amount of money held by British clearance banks could be as
high as 35 million pounds at 1945 prices (about 56 million U.S.
dollars at the current price), according to estimates contained in
the report.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Midland Bank said, "The money is certainly
there. When the accounts were unfrozen at the end of the war, we
wrote to the customers at their last known addresses. Funds that
were not claimed were then recorded in branches' records."
</P>
<P>
Lord Janner has reportedly written to British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook, demanding that where no heir can be found, the money
is paid into humanitarian fund for survivors and their families.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1939 Trading with the Enemy Act, all assests invested
in Britain by "enemy nationals," including victims of the Nazis,
were seized by the Custodian of Enemy Property. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
