<HEADLINE> UNESCO Workshop on Vocation for Girls Opens in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A five-day UNESCO sub-regional
workshop on scientific, technical and vocational education for
girls in Africa opened here today with a theme of "From Theory to
Action".
</P>
<P>
The workshop has attracted 30 participants from Zambia, South
Africa, Swaziland, Lesotho, Mozambique, Botswana, Malawi, Ghana,
Tanzania, Kenya, Namibia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
In her opening remarks, Zimbabwe's Rural Resources and Water
Development Minister Joyce Mujuru said that scientific, technical
and vocational training is a special area which has until
recently been shunned by girls.
</P>
<P>
She said girls tend to take up traditional women's careers
such as teaching and nursing, yet it has been seen that girls
could perform just as well in non-traditional professions.
</P>
<P>
"In Africa, given our particular circumstances, we need to do
even more to ensure the participation of girls in scientific,
technical and vocational education so that they can realize their
full potential while at the same time contributing to the
development process," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said the challenge of participation of girls in
scientific, technical and vocational education is a big one in
Africa, which needs the involvement of all sectors of society.
</P>
<P>
Mujuru said a study in Zimbabwe of the participation of girls
in scientific, technical and vocational education focusing on
disciplines such as science and engineering has found out that in
some of the disciplines, the participation of girls is in some
cases as low as two percent or nil.
</P>
<P>
She said targets were set to bring up women's participation,
but these were not necessarily fulfilled because of various
factors in the socio-cultural environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
