<HEADLINE> EU Ministers likely to Make Little Progress on EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The conference of European
Union (EU) finance ministers, due to be held in Luxembourg later
this week, is not expected to make marked progress over the
European Monetary Union (EMU), according to EU sources.
</P>
<P>
EU monetary officials, who declined to be named, said here
today that no concrete decisions on the planned single European
currency euro would emerge from this gathering.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the press speculation that the conference would
discuss the conversion rates between EU national currencies and
the euro, one official said, "I don't think there is any great
urgency to nail these issues down. Nobody really expects a
clear-cut agreement."
</P>
<P>
"I don't think there will be any discussion about (conversion
rates) at all," he said, adding that there was a strong desire
among EU members not to "rock the boat."
</P>
<P>
Some other officials noted that the EU was under no specific
mandate to come up with a concrete decision on conversion rates
this year.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Luxembourg meeting this weekend would
focus on future economic policy coordination in the euro area as
well as external foreign exchange policy issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
