<HEADLINE> Kuwait Interested in Buying Mine Hunters: Navy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait is considering to
purchase mine hunters to add to its navy, an officer in Kuwait
Navy said today without specifying the number of the boats and the
potential selling countries.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with official Kuwait News Agency (KUNA) on
board the U.S. "USS Dextrous" mine countermeasures ship carrying
out a mission in the Gulf waters, Colonel Hassan Zaidan Al-Enezy
said that "we are still studying the issue of buying mine hunters
through close consultations with our Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) counterparts."
</P>
<P>
GCC, as a regional political and economic organization, groups
Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Oman, Qatar, Bahrain as
well as Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the heavyweight of the GCC organization,
recently received a third British-made mine-sweeping ship equipped
with modern mines detecting and destruction devices to complete
a defense agreement with Britain which stipulates to provide the
Gulf kingdom with three such ships.
</P>
<P>
Al-Enezy said "we need to carry out more studies on the mine
hunters appropriate for our region, waters and weather."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that there have been visits, missions and
training carried out by mine sweepers, clearers and hunters in
Kuwait from its allied countries including the United States.
</P>
<P>
He said units specialized in explosives and mines from the
Kuwaiti navy have undergone constant training since Gulf war
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The officer said although no problems of sea mines occurred
recently, but "we should still be cautious."
</P>
<P>
"This is a problem we must face after the (Gulf) war and one
we must always be prepared to deal with," he said, adding that
the presence of mine sweepers in the area "gives us confidence
when we are out in the water."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, KUNA said the U.S. commander of the mine
countermeasures Squadron Two Forward, Captain Thomas Carlson, said
the purpose of the mission was "to keep the sea lanes safe and
open."
</P>
<P>
Carlson is on a one-day visit to Kuwait to brief and discuss
with Kuwaiti officials their operation and means of cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
