<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Coordinate SADC's Food Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe has been given
task to coordinate a food security directorate of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
The assignment was approved by the Council of Ministers of the
regional group in the Malawi's commercial capital, Blantyre,
ahead of today's summit, the Southern African Broadcasting
Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the new arrangement, Zimbabwe will coordinate animal
diseases, fisheries, marine and wildlife as well as crops.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Minister of Agriculture Kumbirai Kangai said today
in Blantyre that the decision was taken unanimously. Zimbabwe has
played a leading role in ensuring adequate food in the region.
</P>
<P>
Southern Africa has been warned of an impending drought linked
to the El-Nino factor.
</P>
<P>
The sub-regional group which aims at a fully developed common
market by 2000, have 12 members, namely Angola, Botswana,
Lesotho, Malawi, Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa,
Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
