<HEADLINE> Less Car Sales Forecast In Western Europe Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Car sales in Western Europe are
expected to fall to 12.5 million in 2000, compared with 12.8
million last year, according to a leading forecaster.
</P>
<P>
The gap of almost 300,000 vehicles amounts to the annual output
of one big factory or two medium-sized factories.
</P>
<P>
It is expected the chronic gap between excess capacity and
insufficient demand in Europe's motor industry will grow worse
because of higher taxes and rising environmentalism.
</P>
<P>
The economist Intelligence Unit blames the decline on fiscal
stringency as European Union countries attempt to meet the
convergence criteria for starting economic and monetary union in
January 1999.
</P>
<P>
It also blames the growing impact of environmental controls on
car use.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Volkswagen, Vauxhall/Opel and Citroen are
using this week's Frankfurt motor show to launch new models in the
lower-medium-sized car segment.
</P>
<P>
The report accepts industry forecasts that European sales will
rise by about 2.5 percent to slightly more than 13 million units
this year.
</P>
<P>
However, it predicts a steady decline in the subsequent three
years, with the biggest fall taking place in 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
