<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Telecom Cuts National Evening Prices 10 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- British Telecom (BT) is to
reduce the cost of national calls made during weekday evenings and
nights by a further 10 percent from October 1 -- a total 28
percent cut in a year.
</P>
<P>
BT announced today that as part of its latest price cuts, the
cost of these calls will come down from 4.7 percent a minute to
just 4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, BT will reduce the cost of daytime calls made
to Cellnet and Vodafone cellular phones by 12 percent -- from 36.5
percent a minute to 32 percent -- reflecting reductions in
payments which BT makes to the two mobile operators.
</P>
<P>
BT cut national evening and night-time call charges by 20
percent -- from 5.9 percent a minute to 4.7 percent -- in October
last year. At the same time, national daytime calls were cut by 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
This was followed by a further 10 percent cut to national
daytime calls and a 3.8 percent cut to regional daytime calls in
May this year, also simplifying charging by creating a new single
rate for all long distance UK daytime calls.
</P>
<P>
In the past 18 months, BT has also cut the cost of calls to
every country in the world -- some by up to 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
Overall, BT's price cuts over the past four years mean that the
average residential call bill has come down by 32 percent in real
terms while the average business call bill has come down by 35
percent.
</P>
<P>
Local call charges have fallen by about 25 percent in real
terms in that time, regional calls by 27 percent, national calls
by 48 percent and international calls by 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for BT said that the reduction in the cost of calls
to mobile phones would encourage people to make more calls, thus
creating a bigger market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
