<HEADLINE> Iran Calls for Diffusion of Tension in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Iran today called for
diffusion of tension in the world's most sensitive region of
Persian Gulf which boasts of 60 percent of global oil reserves.
</P>
<P>
Addressing foreign ambassadors and representatives of
international organization based in Tehran, Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharrazi said "the Persian Gulf area, having experienced
two consecutive destructive wars in the course of a decade, is
in dire need of urgent tension-diffusing measures."
</P>
<P>
This is the first official statement by the Iranian new
foreign minister since he won the vote of confidence from
Iranian Parliament on August 20.
</P>
<P>
The 53-year-old minister said that "diffusion of tension in
the Persian Gulf not only serves the cause of economic growth
and prosperity in the region but is also beneficial to the rest
of the world."
</P>
<P>
"In other words, peace and tranquility in the Persian Gulf,
which can be best secured through the regional states
themselves, also serve the legitimate interests of the world
community as regards the energy sources in this area," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi noted that "we believe that the Persian Gulf states
are fully capable of arriving at an acceptable arrangement for
regional security through dialogue and cooperation..."
</P>
<P>
The Iranian foreign minister assured the international
community that Iran stands ready to engage in "a serious
dialogue with her neighbors in the Persian Gulf on these and
other similar issues."
</P>
<P>
These issues include establishment of the Persian Gulf as a
zone of peace free from weapons of mass destruction, he added.
</P>
<P>
Diffusion of tension is one of the five-point regional policy
of the new Iranian government headed by President Mohammad
Khatami.
</P>
<P>
However, Kharrazi did not mention what is the source of
tension in the region. Tehran regards the foreign forces led by
the United States in the region as the major threat to its own
national security.
</P>
<P>
The United States currently deploys 22,000 Air Force, Army,
Navy and Marine personnel on 14 ships or at facilities in Saudi
Arabia, Kuwait, Qatar and Bahrain, according to media reports.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. military presence in the Gulf includes the Fifth
Fleet.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about Iran's regional policies, Kharrazi told the
diplomatic corps that Iran's regional policies are formulated
with particular regard for the characteristics of the sensitive
region.
</P>
<P>
"Being situated, on the one hand, in the north of the world's
energy artery in the Persian Gulf and, on the other, to the
south of the newly independent states in the Central Asia, has
bestowed Iran with a particular geo-strategic position," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said "our policy is based on good-neighborliness
and promotion and consolidation of mutual trust through adoption
and pursuance of confidence building measures."
</P>
<P>
He assured Iran's neighboring countries by saying that "the
new administration, in its resolve to further promote mutual
trust and confidence with the neighboring countries, will pursue
these proposals and undertake new initiatives in a more
energetic fashion."
</P>
<P>
To this end, Kharrazi called for cooperation of the regional
states in the field of disarmament and the establishment of the
Middle East as a nuclear weapon free zone.
</P>
<P>
"We are of the opinion that the regional states can further
advance their state of cooperation through confidence building
measures toward reducing arms expenditures and increasing
transparency in military programs," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-08 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
