<HEADLINE> Arab League Pins Peace Hope on Albright's Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) today
pinned hope on U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's
upcoming trip to the Middle East for reviving the stalled peace
process.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released here on eve of Albright's visit, AL
Secretary General Esmat Abdul Meguid expressed the hope that the
visit will contribute to saving the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Albright is scheduled to arrive in Israel Wednesday in her
first trip to the region as secretary of state. She will also
visit Palestinian self-rule area, Jordan, Egypt, Syria and Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Meguid's statement was commenting on the tripartite summit of
Palestinian, Jordanian and Egyptian leaders held here Sunday to
coordinate their stance during Albright's visit.
</P>
<P>
The timing of the summit envisaged a chance for salvaging the
peace process from the dangers that have jeopardized it as a
result of the current Israeli government's practices, he said.
</P>
<P>
The statement highlighted the importance of the signed peace
agreements to the peace process as stressed by Palestinian
National Authority President Yasser Arafat, Jordanian King Hussein
and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in their meeting.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after the summit, the three leaders urged
intensified international efforts to ensure accurate
implementation of all signed agreements and resuscitate the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
While condemning violence and terrorism against civilians, they
urged Israel to refrain from actions alien to the "spirit of
peace." The three leaders also pledged to continue contacts with
parties concerned to help break the stalemate.
</P>
<P>
Meguid also blamed Israel for foiling mediators' efforts in
reviving the deadlocked peace.
</P>
<P>
Albright's talks with the Palestinians and Israelis are
expected to cover security and political matters, with particular
focus on the transitional period and its terms included in deals
signed by both sides.
</P>
<P>
The peace process has been deadlocked since March when Israel
began to build Jewish settlements in East Jerusalem. The
stalemate has been deepened by the suicide bombing attacks in
Jerusalem on July 30 and last Thursday that altogether killed 20
people and wounded more than 360 others, following which Israel
imposed closure on the Palestinian self-rule areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
