of causing escalation of violence in the region.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Information Minister Fuad Faresi was quoted by
Kuwait News Agency as telling reporters in Jeddah after a
cabinet meeting that Israel's arbitrary actions against the
Palestinians and its aggressions against south Lebanon were the
cause of the current violence.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated Saudi position that Israel must implement all
the U.N. resolutions concerning the Middle East peace process and
the peace accords signed with the concerned parties.
</P>
<P>
Faresi said that these are the only ways to end the turmoil of
violence in the region.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the implementation of the U.N. resolutions,
especially resolution 425 which calls for an immediate and
unconditional Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon, would help
ease the tension in the region and pave the way for the
conclusion of just and comprehensive peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi minister said his country rejected terrorism in all
its forms.
</P>
<P>
He announced this Saudi position on the eve of a scheduled
visit to the region by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright this week, her first trip to the troubled region since
she took office in January.
</P>
<P>
Her visit is widely seen as a new U.S. effort to restart the
deadlocked Middle East peace process as a result of the
hard-line policy of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
such as the construction of a new Jewish settlement in East
Jerusalem and the attack against targets in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Tension escalated in the region since last Thursday's triple
suicide bombings in Jerusalem which killed eight people and
wounded 190 others.
</P>
