<HEADLINE> Cyprus Rules out Regional Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government today
rejected the talk of war or hot incidents for Cyprus or the region.
</P>
<P>
Telling reporters here today, Government Spokesman Manolis
Christofides was commenting on the U.S. views on the likelihood of
war in the region and the Turkish threats to strike Cyprus if
Russian missiles are deployed on the island.
</P>
<P>
"A superpower, with world interests, can prevent conflicts and
secure international peace, in cooperation with the U.N., and
study the situation as well as difference between states,"
Christofides said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman restated the Cypriot government's position that
there will be no need to deploy the missiles if Cyprus is
demilitarized or if there is sufficient progress to warrant its
annulment.
</P>
<P>
When these are seen, "neither side, Cyprus or Russia, will
insist on implementing the contract," he said.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, Cyprus contracted to purchase Russian
anti-aircraft missiles, a move which has sparked immense
international reaction.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
</TEXT>
