<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Official on Solution of Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The solution to the
protracted Cyprus issue needs a process and no one should
expect miracles overnight, a senior U.S. official said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Thomas Miller, the U.S. State Department's new Cyprus
coordinator, made the remarks upon arrival here on a shuttle
mission for the Cyprus issue, according to the semi-official
Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Miller said that his Ankara tour aims
to see how a Cyprus settlement could be achieved.
</P>
<P>
He said he would make further trips to Greece and the two
sides of the divided Cyprus to exchange views with the officials
there over the long-standing issue.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that no one should expect too much from the current
negotiations, the U.S. official said that it is extremely
important to understand that the settlement of the Cyprus
dispute is a long and hard process.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when the Turkish
troops invaded and took over the northern third of the island in
the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations and international community have been
working for decades to reunite the divided island, but so far no
concrete results have been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Miller said that he and U.S. Cyprus envoy Richard Holbrooke
would do all they can to push forward the talks, but all sides
concerned should lower their expectations slightly.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot President Glafoks Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktas met last month in Switzerland under the
U.N. sponsorship, but no progress was made.
</P>
<P>
Recently, media reports about delivery of the Russian-made
S-300 missiles to the Cypriot government caused a new wave of
tension on the divided island, also touching off a war of word
between Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Refusing to comment on the S-300 missile deal between Cyprus
and Russia, Miller noted that public accusations could only make
the talks more difficult.
</P>
<P>
Miller is to meet Turkish Foreign Ministry Undersecretary
Onur Oymen and Deputy Undersecretary Inal Batu Tuesday,
media reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
