<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Illiteracy Rate Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 8 (Xinhua) -- There is a fall of
illiteracy rate globally from 45 percent 50 years ago to 23
percent now, according to a UNESCO statement available here
today.
</P>
<P>
The statement was issued by Federico Mayor, Director General
of the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization (UNESCO).
</P>
<P>
"This is a remarkable achievement since over the same period
the world population has continued to grow," said the statement
to mark the International Literacy Day that befalls today.
</P>
<P>
However, the statement said, "the trend in Africa, Asia and
Arab states should not be allowed to take hold."
</P>
<P>
It was referring to the fact that the number of illiterates is
rising in Sub-Saharan Africa, Asia and Arab states with the
illiteracy rate reaching more than 70 percent in 19 countries in
Africa and Asia.
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that although illiteracy could not be
equated with ignorance, it is a major obstacle to the acquisition
of the knowledge and know-how that are essential for daily life
in modern society.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO in the statement pledged to "continue to get engaged in
activities designed to motivate, coordinate and mobilize national
efforts" to increase the literacy rate of the world population.
</P>
<P>
It urged governments to re-double their efforts to spread
adult education and literacy and called for the strengthening of
solidarity between industrialized and developing countries in
this effort. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
