<HEADLINE> S. African Football Boss Optimistic About Hosting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's hopes of
hosting the soccer world cup will be strengthened following the
failure of Cape Town to secure the 2004 Olympic Games, South
African Football Association Boss Danny Jordaan said here today.
</P>
<P>
Cape Town, the legislative capital of South Africa and famous
scenic spot, lost the race to host the 2004 Olympic Games when
the International Olympic Committee gave Athens the nod on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Jordaan, however, felt this could be to soccer's benefit. "We
have registered our bid with FIFA (International Federation of
Football Association), but did not want to talk about it while
Cape Town was bidding for the Olympic Games," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But now that the Cape Town bid is over. We will be discussing
it (soccer bid) at our international board meeting next week,"
Jordaan added.
</P>
<P>
South Africa can point to the success of the 1996 African
Nations Cup Tournament, which was staged at short notice after
Kenya withdrew as hosts in 1995, local football sources said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is one of four countries bidding to stage the
World Cup finals in 2006 with Brazil, England and Germany also in
the race to stage the tournament.
</P>
<P>
France will host the finals next year, while South Korea and
Japan will jointly stage the tournament in 2002.
</P>
<P>
"We are convinced that we will have more than even chance to
get the World Cup to South Africa -- and the continent," Jordaan
said optimistically. 
</P>
</TEXT>
