<HEADLINE> Greece Warns Turkey of Facing More Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Greece today warned Turkey of
more problems it will face in becoming a part of international law
and order.
</P>
<P>
Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas sent out the warning
while commenting on recent statements made by Turkish officials.
</P>
<P>
Reppas said that Turkey was marginalizing itself and would find
itself facing problems in becoming a part of international law and
order.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is not Greek-Turkish but a more general fact that
Turkey does not recognize the general jurisdiction of the court at
the Hague which has been recognized by the whole of the civilized
world," he said.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem reportedly said Sunday that
Ankara rejected a European Union (EU) proposal to take its
differences with Athens to the International Court at the Hague
and asked the union to press Greece to demilitarize the eastern
Aegean islands.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos today also warned Turkey that Greece would raise
the issue of demilitarizing the Bosporus straits if Turkey
persisted in its threat to take Greece to the International Court
at the Hague over the demilitarization of the eastern Aegean
islands.
</P>
<P>
In response to today's statements by Turkish Foreign
Undersecretary Inal Batu calling "irresponsible" Greek Prime
Minister Costas Simitis's response that any attack on Cyprus by
Turkey would be cause for war, Reppas said that Simitis had
outlined a clear position, repeating the positions of Cyprus
President Glafcos Clerides.
</P>
<P>
As for the Madrid communique signed between Greece and Turkey
in recent months, Reppas said that the spirit of the joint
communique was alive but seeking a response from the Turkish side.
</P>
<P>
He also said that expert committees from both countries could
still meet but the scheduled meeting did not take place due to the
"negative climate" created by the recent statements of Turkish
officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
