<HEADLINE> Iran Urges Israel to Return All Rights to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Iran's new government today
announced its stand toward the Middle East crisis, urging Israel
to return all rights to the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi said that the Middle East
crisis can be solved only through the realization of all the
rights of the Palestinian people and other Arab people, in
particular their right to self-determination, return of refugees
and the liberation of the occupied territories, including
Jerusalem, southern Lebanon and the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
Addressing foreign ambassadors and representatives of the
international organizations based in Iran's capital of Tehran,
Kharrazi stressed that "there is no other way out (of the crisis)."
</P>
<P>
He attacked the Israeli regime for creating the crisis through
"decades of oppression of the Palestinian and Lebanese people"
and further aggravating it by carrying out expansionist policies.
</P>
<P>
Although he did not point his finger to a specific state, the
minister criticized some outside powers for seeking to maintain
and expand their influence in the region.
</P>
<P>
He stated that "we are also seeking peace and stability in the
Middle East; a just and lasting peace that would receive regional
consensus and would cure this chronic crisis once and for all."
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Iranian Parliament Vice-Speaker Movahedi Kermani
declared that Iran will continue to support Palestinians in their
struggle against Israel.
</P>
<P>
He said that the defeat of the Israeli commandos in southern
Lebanon would one day lead to the total collapse of the Israeli
regime.
</P>
<P>
Twelve Israeli soldiers were killed and four others wounded
last Friday when Lebanese army and resistance fighters of
Iranian-backed Hezbollah and the Shiite movement Amal ambushed a
16-member Israeli commando who landed on the village of Nsariyyeh,
about 45 kilometers north of the Israeli border in an attempt to
explode an Amal base near the village. 
</P>
