<HEADLINE> Congo (K), Seychelles Taken as SADC Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLANTYRE (Malawi), September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic
Republic of Congo (former Zaire), and the Seychelles were given
greenlight to join the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) at the SADC summit here today.
</P>
<P>
SADC leaders agreed that the two countries which have formally
applied to join the regional group satisfied the criteria for
admission of new members, according to a communique of the
one-day SADC summit.
</P>
<P>
Their admission has increased the number of SADC member states
to 14.
</P>
<P>
Kaire Mbuende, SADC executive secretary said at the closing
ceremony of the southern African group summit that the two
members have tremendous potential to benefit the region through
their active participation in SADC programs.
</P>
<P>
Mbuende expressed optimism that efforts of Kabila government
to usher in a new era of political stability in the economic
reconstruction would be successful.
</P>
<P>
Nelson Mandela, SADC Chairman and President of South Africa,
said at the end of the summit that he is fully confident of the
democratic process in the Democratic Republic of Congo, where
election is expected in one or two years.
</P>
<P>
Congo (K) has major strategic significance to the region as it
shares borders with several SADC countries and has potential to
cooperate with the group in key sectors such as energy, water,
tourism, transport and communications, the summit communique
said.
</P>
<P>
Congo (K) which emerged more than three months ago after
Laurent Kabila forced out the newly-died former president Mobutu
Sese Seko, will make the natural rich region stronger with its
abundant mineral resources.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the two new member countries are expected to attend
the 1998 SADC summit in Mauritius. 
</P>
</TEXT>
