<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eleven Million Children Die Each Year Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- More than 11 million
children die each year before reaching the age of five all over
the world, according to a World Health Organization (WHO) report
released here today.
</P>
<P>
Around 8 million children, about 70 percent of the 11 million
little children dying each year, die from one or more of five
causes: pneumonia, dirrhoea, measles, malaria and malnutrition,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, WHO believes that many of these deaths can be
prevented through Integrated Management of Childhood Illness
(IMCI), an approach developed by WHO in collaboration with UNICEF.
</P>
<P>
WHO and UNICEF will highlight the urgent need to put the IMCI
strategy into practice at an international meeting in Santo
Momingo, Dominican Republic, from 9 to 12 September.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 countries have begun to implement the IMCI
strategy at regional and local levels since treatment guidelines
and training materials first became available in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of many of them will provide the conference
with successful case histories of using IMCI methods to improve
the care of sick children with the aim of reducing child
mortality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
