<HEADLINE> OAU Calls on UNITA to Abide by Peace Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African
Unity (OAU) today called on Angola's National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) to abide by a 1994 peace accord to
end the country's civil war, Zambia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
OAU Secretary General Salim Ahmed Salim told the delegates at
a Southern African Development Community (SADC) summit in
Blantyre, Malawi that economic integration in southern Africa
continues to be hampered by conflicts.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the southern African countries are seriously
disturbed by UNITA's refusal to fully comply with the provisions
of the Lusaka protocol signed in 1994, which constitutes a factor
of destabilization in Angola, he said.
</P>
<P>
Salim urged the UNITA to "scrupulously" abide by the Lusaka
protocol and operate in accordance with the spirit and letter of
the government of national unity established after general
elections at the end of 1992.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA and the government dominated by the People's
Liberation Movement of Angola (MPLA) signed a peace treaty in
November, 1994 in the capital of Zambia to end the country's two
decades of war.
</P>
<P>
Angola is the only country in southern Africa which is still
directly threatened by a civil war.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the U.N. Security Council has warned the UNITA to
honor its obligations in the peace plan or face sanctions from
September 30, which would include curbs on UNITA members' travel
outside Angola and closure of the organization's offices abroad.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the two-day SADC summit, Salim stressed that
conflicts are threatening to destroy the social fabric of the
societies with significant impact on the socio-economic
development of the African countries.
</P>
<P>
The SADC members hold a summit annually. This afternoon, the
summit made a declaration on gender equality, which emphasizes
that women should obtain equality, respect and dignity as men
through their full participation in social activities, according
to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
