<HEADLINE> U.S. F-22 Stealth Fighter Tests Flight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States new
stealth fighter, F-22 Raptor, made a test flight Sunday at speeds
up to 360 kilometers per hour, the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
After an hour of flying in the F-22 Raptor over northwestern
Georgia, pilot Paul Metz said that there was no problem with the
airplane.
</P>
<P>
The plane's maiden flight was closely monitored by two F-16s
which tailed the F-22 and 24 engineers on the ground as Metz
tested the craft's handling at various speeds and altitudes.
</P>
<P>
The jet was built by Lockheed Martin Aeronautical Systems in
partnership with the Boeing Company and Pratt &AMP; Whitney.
</P>
<P>
The F-22 has an innovative computer system that shows the pilot
all the data on one screen instead of presenting it on several
monitors. The plane also is much easier and cheaper to maintain.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force expects to get 339 of the planes to replace the
F-15C, currently its top fighter, at a cost of 43 billion U.S.
dollars. The first squadron is expected tobe in operation by
2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
