<HEADLINE> US Airlines Raise Ticket Prices to Record Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Major U.S. airlines raised
already record-high ticket prices by 5 percent nearly across-the
board, a sign of rebust bookings for the fall and the strong
economy, The Wall Street Journal reported today.
</P>
<P>
Business travelers will take the brunt of the increases. But
the newspaper also said many advance-purchase fares were raised
over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Northwest Airlines initiated the industry-wide price hike when
it raised its unrestricted coach fares by 5 percent Thursday.
American Airlines and United Airlines quickly followed suit, as
did several other major carriers, including Delta Air Lines on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"There are some exceptions market-by-market, but the majority
of fare types are up 5 percent," an spokesman for American
Airlines told the paper.
</P>
<P>
Airline passenger traffic in the U.S. hit record high over the
Summer and carriers said that early fall bookings are at least
equal to last year, which was a strong travel period. 
</P>
