<HEADLINE> Egypt Extends Reserved Welcome to Albright's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said today that Cairo welcomes U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright's upcoming visit on the basis of her promised
balance in approaching the Mideast peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters today, Moussa said that Albright's visit,
which is the first since she assumed her post earlier this year,
is important, in light of Washington's role as a sponsor of peace.
</P>
<P>
She is expected to help revive the stalled peace process with a
major U.S. initiative. However, the six-month peace stalemate,
compounded by recent waves of suicide bombings and violence as
well as Israeli reprisals, threatens to make the high-profile
U.S. mission a flop.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said Egypt views Albright's visit in light of her recent
speech at the National Press Club that contained the promise of a
balanced approach in peace mediation.
</P>
<P>
"It is on this basis that we will receive Albright," he added.
</P>
<P>
In the August 6 speech in Washington, Albright reiterated that
the "sine qua non for progress is a mutual commitment to security
and against violence."
</P>
<P>
Israel held Palestinians responsible for Thursday's triple
bombing attack in Jerusalem, the second in five weeks, and
reimposed harsh closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip. It has
also refused to hand over more land to Palestinians unless Arafat
cracks down on Muslim militants.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said the current situation was not created by only one
party, but is rather the result of Israeli policies that have
frustrated the Palestinian people and instigated the violence.
</P>
<P>
Washington is speaking in Israeli tune that before anything,
the PNA must exert itself "100 percent" -- in the word of the
State Department -- to combat terrorism.
</P>
<P>
An urgent Egyptian-Jordanian-PNA summit on Sunday was intended
to strike "the important balance in rejuvenating the peace process
to safeguard the rights of all parties," Moussa told reporters.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Gaza, Arafat will meet with Albright
in the West Bank town of Jericho in the first stop of her
multi-leg tour that may also take her to Israel, Jordan, Egypt,
Syria and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb Erekat said today the talks
in Jericho will cover security and political matters, with
particular focus on the transitional period and terms included in
deals signed with Israel.
</P>
<P>
He said it was agreed that Albright's agenda covers security,
settlement, final status talks and the land-for-peace
principle. U.S. officials have promised that Albright will not
offer a proposal under which the final status talks will be
resumed at the expense of the transitional stage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
