<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC to Take Action in Mining, Education, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLNATYRE (MALAWI), September 8 (Xinhua) -- The one-day summit
of the Southern African Development Community (SADC), held here
in the southern Malawian city today, passed protocols on mining,
educaiton and eduction for future joint actions.
</P>
<P>
The protocol on mining provides for the harmonization of
national and regional policies, strategies and programs in the
mineral-rich sub-region, according to the communique issued after
the summit late this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The summit agreed that the ultimate objective of the protocol
was to promote inter-dependence and integration of the region's
mining industry with a view to enhancing its competitiveness and
increasing the regions's share in international mineral markets.
</P>
<P>
The education and training protocol, on the other hand,
provides a policy framework that allows the SADC region to
progressively move towards equivalence, harmonization and
eventual standardization of member states in education and
training systems, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
The group's summit decided that areas of cooperation will
cover the development and formulation of coherent education and
training policies, basic education, intermediate education and
training, high education and training, research and development,
as well as publishing and library services.
</P>
<P>
Education, as part of the human resources development plan,
got repeated emphasis by Nelson Mandela, SADC Chairman and
President of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The summit stressed that the inter-dependence among the SADC
member states could help guarantee a quicker and sustainable
development.
</P>
<P>
The summit urged its group members to join hands for a
sub-regional integration.
</P>
<P>
The summit was satisfied with the economic development of the
region in the past year, saying that member states have generally
adopted pragmatic policies aimed at fostering financial
stability, private sector participation and market-let economy.
</P>
<P>
The 12-member group decided to take the Democratic Republic of
Congo and Seychelles to be their new members, boostering its
strength in mineral and tourism industries.
</P>
<P>
SADC is to hold its next annual summit in Mauritius, the
island country on Indian Ocean. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
