<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Reform Pension System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government is
mounting a major public-relations effort in a bid to radically
reform the country's public pension system this fall.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Paul Martin is expected to introduce
wide-ranging pension legislation within the first few weeks of the
new parliament, which will open on September 22.
</P>
<P>
The legislation package would overhaul the Canada/Quebec
Pension Plan according to an agreement and a timetable worked out
with the provinces.
</P>
<P>
It also includes a new Seniors Benefit to replace old-age
security and the guaranteed income supplement, a report said
today.
</P>
<P>
As the centerpiece of the Liberal government's fall legislation
agenda, the planned bills would yield the most fundamental changes
to Canada's retirement-income system since the Canada Pension Plan
was introduced in 1966.
</P>
<P>
The changes would make seniors with family incomes of less than
40,000 dollars (28,000 USD) moderately better off, and cut the
current overall benefits to middle- and upper-income Canadians.
</P>
<P>
And the benefits would be based on family income rather than on
individual income.
</P>
<P>
The federal government expects that the new plan will reduce
the cost of seniors benefits by 10 percent by 2030 from what they
would have been otherwise.
</P>
<P>
The government is saying that the changes are necessary to put
the retirement system on a firmer footing before the big baby-boom
generation begins retiring in 2011.
</P>
<P>
By 2030, when the last boomers hit retirement age, there will
be an estimated 8.8 million Canadians over 65, compared with 3.7
million now.
</P>
<P>
The previous conservative Canadian government attempted to cut
pension benefits, but was forced by public anger to back off in
1985.
</P>
<P>
Critics argue that the new plan actually discourages savings
and will hurt future middle-class retirees.
</P>
<P>
"There are some misconceptions, and it is very important to
clear up the misconceptions and that is what the government is in
the process of doing," Martin said.
</P>
<P>
"It's simply a question of getting the facts right," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties are seizing upon the chance to launch
another round of attacks on the Liberal government.
</P>
<P>
The proposed system will undermine the willingness of Canadians
to save for their own old age because of the steep reduction in
benefits as incomes rise, the Reform Party argues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
