<HEADLINE> Iran Unveils New Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Iran announced here today its
new foreign policy, highlighting "independence", "dialogue"
and "cooperation" with the outside world.
</P>
<P>
"We will maintain relations with any government that truly
respects our independence and refrains from interference in our
internal affairs," said Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi
while addressing foreign ambassadors and representatives of
international organizations based in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
He said Iran does not seek domination or pursue expansionist
policies and rejects the same from others, adding that "one of
the most fundamental achievements of our revolution for which our
people sacrificed tremendously is Iran's independence."
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi called on all the countries to closely cooperate and
participate in the search for solutions to international problems
in the world at the entrance of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
He said Iran is prepared to participate, and would play a
positive and constructive role in the process.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi voiced urgent need for preventing tensions and
conflicts, calling for dialogue, understanding, tolerance and
observance of international laws and the U.N. Charter, encouraging
states to resolve their differences and conflicts through
negotiations and peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that instead of pointing finger at each other, we
should engage in dialogue." he said.
</P>
<P>
He called on the international community to counter unilateral
economic sanctions which he called "indeed run against the will of
the international community," and should thereby be prevented from
spreading of this dangerous practice. He did not point his finger
at the United States.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi called for wider economic cooperation with other
countries, saying Iran, situated in the heart of a vital
geo-strategic area of the world, is a secure and promising
economic and trading partner, with commitments and dedication to
regional and global cooperation, peace and security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
