<HEADLINE> Kenya's IPPG Committee Makes Progress in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A Committee on Constitutional
Reforms in Kenya has made progress on the issue of minimum
reforms to be taken to facilitate free and fair elections during
the forthcoming General Elections.
</P>
<P>
George Anyona, Secretary of the committee set up last
Wednesday by the Inter-Parties Parliamentary Group (IPPG), was
addressing a press conference here this evening.
</P>
<P>
He said that the committee would hold consultations with
Kenyan head of state, religious leaders and others on the minimum
reforms of Kenya's constitution before the General Elections to
be held later this year.
</P>
<P>
The Co-Chairman of the committee Kiraitu Murungi pointed out
that a unanimous decision had been reached on a number of reforms
including new clauses to be introduced into the constitution.
</P>
<P>
The committee was in agreement that a definite date be set for
future general elections so that people could know before and get
prepared for the elections, he added.
</P>
<P>
Murungi noted that an overhaul of the drafted constitutional
review bill had been completed and amendments to that bill would
be introduced and presented to the plenary session to be held
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
If adopted, he said, a new bill to amend the constitution of
Kenya would be drafted and subsequently be subjected to debate in
the seventh parliament.
</P>
<P>
Three technical committee were set up at the IPPG second
meeting held here last week with a mandate to make
recommendations including constitutional, legal and
administrative reforms,
</P>
<P>
More than 100 members of parliament from the ruling Kenya
African National Union and the Opposition held the first meeting
on August 28 at which the IPPG was formed to take up their
parliamentary roles to spearhead the reforms dialogue between the
ruling and opposition parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
