<HEADLINE> Malawi Appeals for Urgent Food Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Malawian President Bakili
Muluzi today appealed to other members of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) for urgent food aid to his country.
</P>
<P>
Muluzi made this appeal at the 17th SADC summit being held in
Malawi's commercial capital Blantyre amid reports that his
country faces a shortfall of 288,000 tons of grain because of the
El Nino phenomenon, according to Zambia News Agency today.
</P>
<P>
The SADC holds a summit every year in a bid to coordinate its
action to strive for the integration of the regional economies.
</P>
<P>
"With this kind of food shortfall, Malawi will certainly need
assistance to meet the food needs of its people. In this regard,
I will welcome any assistance that is available among us," he
said at the opening of the annual summit.
</P>
<P>
The Malawian president explained that Malawi's latest crop
estimates indicate that food production has declined by 31
percent compared to the harvest in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Weather patterns in the region point to the re-emergence of
the El Nino phenomenon which was responsible for the drought in
Ethiopia that caused a serious famine in 1984.
</P>
<P>
Weather and agriculture officials predict that besides South
Africa and Zimbabwe, the strongest economies in the region, other
regional countries are likely to be devastated by an imminent
drought. Therefore, most SADC countries would have shortfalls of
grain this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
