<HEADLINE> Germany Expects Additional Tax Shortfall in 1997, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- German governments at federal,
state and municipal levels were facing a further 10 billion marks
(5.6 billion U.S. dollars) in tax shortfall this year in addition
to an earlier estimate of 18 billion (10 billion dollars), a
newspaper report said today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Berliner Zeitung newspaper, the federal
government in Bonn alone were expecting an additional shortfall in
tax revenues of five billion marks (2.8 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The report was later confirmed by budget experts in Bonn. But
they noted that the Bonn government had already taken
precautionary measures in order to ensure that Germany's budget
deficit would not be widened further.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry in Bonn, however, dismissed the newspaper
report as speculations.
</P>
<P>
A ministry spokesman said in a statement that it was still too
early to make realistic estimate about tax revenues at the moment.
The next official tax estimate is scheduled for November.
</P>
<P>
A widening tax shortfall would put additional burden on the
German government as it is struggling to meet the fiscal criteria
required for joining the planned single European currency, the
Euro.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to government projections, most experts expect that
Germany's budget deficit is likely to be slightly above the Euro
limit of three percent of gross domestic product (GDP) in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
