<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Australian 500cc world
motorcycle championship rider Anthony Gobert denied taking drugs
Tuesday and said he was upset about being sacked by Suzuki for a
posiest to an unspecified banned substance.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old said the test result, taken by the team and not
the sport's governing body, would be questioned and his family was
seeking legal advice because details of the results had not been
released.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the International Motorcycling Federation (FIM)
said Tuesday that the world body could impose a two-year ban for a
first offence involving certain banned substances.
</P>
<P>
But the spokesman admitted not knowing what substance Suzuki's
tests had allegedly found.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued through Gobert's mother and manager Sue
Gobert on Tuesday said it had been claimed it was for marijuana
but the rider denied using it.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, Gobert said he was "absolutely devastated" by
the sacking and "bitterly disappointed" he was not told before it
was announced to the media.
</P>
<P>
"I have been tested a number of times, both by my team and the
FIM governing body this year and each result came back clear,"
Gobert said in the statement.
