<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Conglomerate's Affiliates Face Bankruptcy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Six affiliates of the ailing
Jinro Group, South Korea's 19th biggest conglomerate, faced
bankruptcy today after failing to honour bills returned to banks.
</P>
<P>
The affiliates are the group's liquor-making flagship Jinro
Ltd., Jinro Coor Brewery Co., Jinro General Foods Co., Jinro
Construction, Jinro International Co., and Jinro Mass Merchandise
Inc.
</P>
<P>
They were pronounced bankrupt after they failed to honour bills
worth 3.25 billion won (3.58 million U.S. dollars), which were
returned to nine banks.
</P>
<P>
The six affiliates filed applications for composition with
provincial district courts Monday to work out a repayment schedule
acceptable to creditors.
</P>
<P>
Jinro's liabilities will be frozen once its application for
court mediation is accepted.
</P>
<P>
But bank officials said that most of Jinro's 52 creditors,
including the main creditor Commercial Bank of Korea, will likely
agree with Jinro's request for composition, as they do not want to
see Jinro go bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
The companies, however, can only operate with cash because
their current deposit account will be closed to block the issuance
of bills.
</P>
<P>
The Jinro Group, with debts of over 3 trillion won, was
described by its creditor banks as a beneficiary of the
anti-bankruptcy pact on April 28.
</P>
<P>
Under the pact, Jinro implemented a self-rescue package worth
1.2 trillion won, including the disposal of real-estate holdings
and sharp curtailment in the number of affiliates and work force.
</P>
<P>
However, due to the ongoing slump in the domestic real estate
market, Jinro has succeeded in mobilizing only 216.8 billion won
so far, falling far short of the planned target. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bomb Threats Hound Philippine Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine capital was
terrified today as many offices, including that of Manila
Archbishop Jaime Cardinal Sin, received bomb threats.
</P>
<P>
An unidentified man called the Archbishop's office this morning
and told office personnel that a bomb had been planted in that
office, local television reports said.
</P>
<P>
Later, the country's sugar center and central postal office
received similar bomb threats. Police were called to the three
places but no bomb was found.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Philippine Stock Exchange today beefed up its
security measures after receiving two bomb threats Monday.
</P>
<P>
These days, Manila has been gripped by fear after two separate
blasts killed six people and wounded 60 others in the capital area
last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A shadowy military group later claimed responsibility for the
bombings and threatened with more offensives should opposition to
President Fidel Ramos' re-election plan persists.
</P>
<P>
The bombings prompted the opposition and the Roman Catholic
Church to accuse Ramos of creating instability by allowing
planting bombs in cities to provide an excuse for imposing martial
law.
</P>
<P>
Ramos bluntly rejected the accusations Monday, saying he had no
intention of proclaiming martial law and elections would proceed
as scheduled in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the explosions, the authorities put law-enforcement
forces in the capital city on high alert against any more
terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ramos and Sin met tonight for the third time in two
weeks in order to ease the tension surrounding the issue of
constitutional change.
</P>
<P>
Ramos is expected to persuade the influential archbishop to
call off the September 21 anti-charter-change protest rally, while
Sin is said to try to ask for a promise from Ramos to take a
clear-cut position against the charter change move.
</P>
<P>
There are no immediate reports about the outcome of the meeting
which was also attended by some leading opponents and proponents
of the charter change move.
</P>
<P>
Sin, who has been strongly opposed to changing the charter to
lift the term limit of Ramos, is planning to organize a massive
rally in central Manila on September 21 to protest the charter
change drive.
</P>
<P>
Under the country's Constitution, Ramos can only serve one
single six-year term, and must step down in June 1998 when his
term expires. 
</P>
</TEXT>
