<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers:
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- As many as 400 people drowned before dawn on Monday when a
packed Haitian ferry tipped over as passengers crowded to one side
in a rush to get off. It was one of the worst maritime disasters
in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
-- NATO troops and hundreds of Bosnian Serbs were locked in a
tense confrontation in several Bosnian towns Monday when the
troops stopped 80 bus loads of Serbs heading for a political rally
in Banja Luka.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- Suits have been filed by state and provincial governments in
Canada and the United States seeking redress from each other in a
dispute over salmon fishing. Fishermen and officials from the
province of British Columbia filed suit in Seattle, accusing the
United States of violating a 1985 treaty by overfishing in
the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
-- The Clinton Administration approved exploratory oil drilling
on Federal land in Utah, where President Clinton last year erected
a national monument to prevent the rich wilderness from
industrial development.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- The Justice Department is dropping charges against a Saudi
dissident suspected of a role in last year's bombing in Dhahran
that killed 19 U.S. servicemen. The department will seek to
extradite him to Saudi Arabia. The charges he faced were unrelated
to that bombing.
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton is delaying a formal verdict on the 368.5
billion dollar tobacco settlement until at least next week, as
heightened anti-tobacco sentiment in Congress underscores the
fragility of the accord between the industry, states and
public-health groups. 
</P>
