<HEADLINE> FIFA: Inter Milan must Pay Extra Money for Ronaldo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVE, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Inter Milan will have to pay
Barcelona an extra dlrs 1.8 million for Brazilian football
superstar Ronaldo, the world soccer governing body FIFA said
Tuesday in Zurich, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Named as FIFA's Player of the Year in January, Ronaldo was
already the world's most expensive soccer player. The decision
raises to about dlrs 28 million the amount paid Barcelona for the
release.
</P>
<P>
This is in addition to Inter Milan's signing bonus to Ronaldo
of dlrs 14 million and an annual salary of dlrs 3 million.
</P>
<P>
FIFA rejected the Italian club's appeal lion pesetas (about
dlrs 26 million) already given Barcelona for releasing Ronaldo
from his eight-year contract.
</P>
<P>
A three-member appeal panel ruled that part of the high sum
already paid by Inter for the 20-year-old forward was to be
regarded as a form of compensation, a statement from FIFA said.
</P>
<P>
The panel said its decision is final.
</P>
<P>
After transferring to Barcelona before last season, Ronaldo led
the Spanish league in scoring with 34 goals. England's Alan
Shearer, who moved from Blackburn Rovers to Newcastle for 15
million pounds (dlrs 25 million) last year but is now injured, was
considered to have been the most expensive transfer in the history
of the sport before Ronaldo's move. 
</P>
</TEXT>
