<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- France today called on factions
of the Congo Republic to continue peace talks on national
reconciliation in Libreville and refrain from sinking deeper into
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The search for a consensual solution (by Congolese factions)
remains essential," said French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques
Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
He declined to comment on the nomination by Congolese President
Pascal Lissouba of Brazzaville Mayor Bernard Kolelas as prime
minister, a move strongly condemned by Lissouba's rival General
Denis Sassou Nguesso, who called it "a choice of war."
</P>
<P>
"The decision of President Lissouba does not demand particular
comment from us," said Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to all the Congolese parties "to work in the spirit
of openness and do nothing which could thwart the on-going
mediation."
</P>
<P>
Gabonese President Omar Bongo and United Nations envoy Mohamed
Sahnoun are mediating the talks among Congolese factions on the
establishment of a government of national union to prepare for the
presidential election and run the country in the transitional
period. 
