<HEADLINE> Private, Foreign Investments Increase in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Both private and foreign
investments have increased in Bangladesh at a reasonable pace due
to pursuance of a liberal industrial policy and gradual
deregulation of the economy, a local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Board of Investment (BOI), the total number of
industries registered with BOI in the first six months of 1996-97
fiscal year stood at 670, the weekly newspaper Economic Times
said.
</P>
<P>
Of the registered industries, 602 were local industries, while
68 were joint ventures and fully foreign direct investment (FDI)
projects, the newspaper added.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, total investment proposals stood at
124.24 billion taka (about 2.82 billion U.S. dollars) in value,
the newspaper stated, adding that the total value of local
investment proposals was 120.15 billion taka (about 2.79 billion
dollars), while that of fully FDI was 3.90 billion taka (about 886
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment was worth 6.40 billion taka (about 145
million dollars) during the same period, the newspaper reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
