<HEADLINE> International Forum on South Korea's Economy Scheduled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 9 (Xinhua) -- An international forum will be
held in Seoul on September 10-11 to discuss South Korea's role in
the world economy, the event's organizers said today.
</P>
<P>
During the Korea Summit '97, participants will focus on South
Korea's changing status in the world economy, particularly since
its entry into the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development (OECD).
</P>
<P>
The summit is organized by the International Herald Tribune and
jointly sponsored by South Korea's Samsung, Hyundai and Daewoo
groups.
</P>
<P>
About 600 prominent figures representing political, academic,
journalistic and corporate communities will attend the event.
</P>
<P>
President Kim Young-sam will deliver a keynote speech on the
second day of the meeting, while government ministers and Hyundai
Group Chairman Chung Mong-koo will also make speeches.
</P>
<P>
Foreign guests at the Korea Summit will include renowned U.S.
futurologist Alvin Toffler, Japanese-born U.S. corporate
strategist Kenichi Omae, OECD Secretary General Donald Johnston
and Uzbekistan Prime Minister Utkur Sultanov.
</P>
<P>
These dignitaries are expected to shed new perspectives on
South Koreans' ongoing struggle for reform and development amid
rapidly changing global order, the organizers said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the International Herald Tribune has held 12
similar international economic forums in eight Asian countries,
including Malaysia, China and Singapore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
