<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Guns Fire at Nigerian Jet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Panic gripped the capital
Freetown Monday evening when over half a dozen heavy
anti-aircraft guns opened fire at a Nigerian air force jet which
streaked across the sky at high altitude.
</P>
<P>
The jet returned to the Nigerian contingent base at Sierra
Leonean grounds of State House and six other locations in the
west and east of the city.
</P>
<P>
Military Leader Major Johnny Paul Koroma was visiting victims
of the recent stray shells at the main hospital in the city when
the jet flew.
</P>
<P>
State House aides told Xinhua later in a telephone interview,
"the Head of State Views the development as another example of
gross violation of our airspace resulting in the apparent loss of
civilian lives."
</P>
<P>
The shootings caused hundreds of market women to abandon their
wares, overturning their goods such as salt and rice as they
dashed for cover.
</P>
<P>
Security has been strengthened after a Nigerian jet launched a
rocket attack on a Pakistani ship at the port here discharging
rice Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
As part of the west African peace keeping force, Nigerian
soldiers are enforcing a blockade and sanctions against Sierra
Leone to compel the junta to return power to the legitimate
government it toppled on May 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
