<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Better Life Means More Coronary Heart Disease In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- An estimated ten million cases
of coronary heart disease have occurred in China so far this year,
mainly because of an improved standards of living.
</P>
<P>
At Fuwai Heart Hospital in Beijing, during the Second Symposium
on Interventional Cardiology, a doctor reports that the main
reason for this increase is simply that people are better of now.
</P>
<P>
"Since China's reforms and opening up to the outside world, the
quality of the people's life has improved substantially and
steadily. People eat more meat and become plump," he
acknowledged. In some large cities like Beijing and Shanghai,
there are even instances of people in their early twenties
suffering from the disease.
</P>
<P>
Coronary heart disease is going to surpass cancer as the major
health threat for Chinese. The number of deaths caused by the
disease is more than 30 per 100,000 in cities and nearly 20 per
100,000 in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Coronary heart disease used to be referred to as "the rich
man's disease" in China because only the rich people could afford
to eat rich food, but things clearly differ now. And, doctors warn
that people should become more aware of their weight and should
eat more reasonably. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
