<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Trade Deficit Drops in July, August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's trade deficit
fell by 140 million U.S. dollars during July and August this year
as compared to the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed here today at a briefing to Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif on trade and finance, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
The briefing, which was also attended by Finance Minister
Sartaj Aziz and Commerce Minister Mohammad Ishaq Dar, was meant to
review the country's economic situation during the last two
months, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
Sharif was briefed on the situation of import, export, foreign
exchange reserves and revenue collection, according to the
sources.
</P>
<P>
Sharif expressed his satisfaction over the improvement in all
the mentioned areas of the economy, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Federal Bureau of Statistics of Pakistan, the
country's trade deficit in fiscal year 1996-1997, which ended on
June 30, stood at 3.37 billion U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
