<HEADLINE> Indian Opposition Leaders to be Charged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A court in Uttar state of
northwestern India today decided to file charges against the
president of the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), the biggest
opposition party in India, and 48 others in connection with the
demolition of a controversial mosque that triggered nation-wide
violence in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said this evening that special judge J. P.
Srivastava will file charges against BJP President L. K. Advani
and the others, including some other BJP leaders, for rioting,
inciting violence and creating hatred between Hindu and Muslim
communities.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people were killed and injured in violence and
riots throughout the country following the demolition of Babri
Basjid mosque in Ayodhya in Uttar on December 6, 1992.
</P>
<P>
The court will begin formal procedures of filing the charges on
October 17, which is also the date for personal appearance for all
the accused.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bureau of Investigation (CBI), which was entrusted
with the investigation into the demolition of the Ayodhya mosque,
has filed a charge sheet after examining 600-more people. In its
charge sheet, the CBI said that the "conspiracy" to demolish the
mosque was hatched with the support of the then Uttar state
government headed by Kalyan Singh.  
</P>
</TEXT>
