<HEADLINE> GCC to Unify Penalty Against Drug Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) member states are drafting a law to unify their
penalties against drug smugglers and dealers, a GCC anti-narcotics
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The draft law is "under discussion" and is expected to be
issued within two years, Maged Ibrahim Maged Al Khalifa, head of
the Qatari delegation at the 11th meeting of directors of
anti-narcotics departments in GCC countries, told the press.
</P>
<P>
A GCC legal committee is following up the draft law which will
be issued by the GCC's General Secretariat, said the Qatari
official who also presides over the three-day meeting, which will
conclude Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The draft law forms part of the efforts to set up a unified
penalty system in GCC member states against drug smugglers and
traders, which can reach death penalty, he added.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, which groups Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates,
Qatar, Kuwait, Bahrain and Oman, has been combating drug menace
through joint actions for years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
