<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investigation on Diana's Death Moving Slowly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Investigation into the death of
Princess Diana is moving ahead slowly, while investigators are
inclined to believe that the crash of the Mercedes was caused by
overspeeding and alcohol consumption by the driver.
</P>
<P>
The daily le Figaro said today that the criminal brigade of the
French police force in charge of the investigation ruled out
several hypotheses, which includes mechanical failure of the
Mercedes S-280 and use of drugs in the car.
</P>
<P>
Police are also confident that two previous examinations made
to discover the amount of alcohol in the bloodstream of the car's
chauffeur, Henri Paul, were correct.
</P>
<P>
The two examinations revealed that the amount of alcohol in
Paul's bloodstream was at least three times higher than the legal
limit.
</P>
<P>
The result of the third blood/alcohol test on Paul will be
announced today. Police are not expecting any new surprises, le
Figaro quoted police sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Police said charges of negligence could be brought against the
Hotel Ritz, which is owned by the family of Dodi al Fayed, the
Egyptian millionaire who was also killed in the car crash, for
"endangering the life of another person" by allowing Paul to drive
the car.
</P>
<P>
Experts examining the car-wreck and the route of the vehicle
will determine in the coming weeks the cause for the abrupt
braking of the car in the Alma tunnel, which was made by the
driver some 16 meters from the site of the crash, as well as the
speed of the car at that time, which is estimated at 180
kilometers per hour (110 miles per hour).
</P>
<P>
Investigators said the body of Dodi al Fayed was autopsied and
toxicological tests made after being returned to England on August
31. But no test results were published before the body was buried.
</P>
<P>
The body of Diana was immediately transferred to the British
embassy after she died in hospital on August 31, and no autopsy
was performed in France because of the so-called "complications in
the diplomatic field."
</P>
<P>
Police say they believe the testimony of an FM radio reporter
who said his car was passed by Diana's car at the entry of Alma
tunnel. He said her car was traveling at a speed of around 160
kilometers per hour (100 miles per hour).
</P>
<P>
Investigators excluded testimony given by an unemployed Rouen
port worker, Francois Levi, who claimed that he saw
motorcycle-riding photographers passing the car in the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
They also excluded a theory that a car ahead of the Mercedes
was trying to slow it down to let photographers take pictures. The
only car caught by police in the tunnel was a Renault driven by
photographer Fabrice Chassery, who arrived at the scene minutes
after the crash.
</P>
<P>
Police said no testimony by rescue workers or doctors had
confirmed the rumors that photograpahers had touched or moved the
body of Diana after the crash took place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
