<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt Urged to Develop Packaging Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
been urged to develop the country's packaging industry to make it
competitive, the Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a study from the Board of Investments as
saying the industry faces stiff competition from Korea, India and
other ASEAN countries like Thailand and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The study showed the industry has been dependent on importation
of packaging products due to outmoded equipment and high cost of
imported machinery and raw materials.
</P>
<P>
The value of imported packaging products increased to 103.63
million U.S. dollars in 1995 from 78.61 million dollars in 1994
and 57.36 million dollars in 1993, it showed.
</P>
<P>
High cost of money rendered packaging firms and end-users
unable to upgrade their equipment as often as competitor
countries, it said.
</P>
<P>
The industry also has been losing with its competitors due to
poor quality of packaging which is the result of market niching
and the pressure to engage in price competition.
</P>
<P>
Also, some of the government's policies primarily on tariff
duties have been affecting the industry.
</P>
<P>
To address these problems, the industry has to develop
environment-friendly packaging products like the waste paper-based
recyclable inner cushion packaging product project.
</P>
<P>
Local firms have started to adapt to trends which are seen to
dominate the world packaging market such as aseptic packaging,
retort pouches and bar coding, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
