<HEADLINE> Computerized Network Improves Customs Efficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The installation of a computer
network has significantly improved the efficiency of customs
procedures in Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
The network currently links 32 land and sea ports of entry in
Shandong and has eliminated redundancies in terms of customs checks
and declarations.
</P>
<P>
Export goods were formerly subject to customs procedures
carried out by various customs offices, with the process repeated
at ports of entry prior to shipments leaving the country.
</P>
<P>
Provincial officials say all the ports of entry in Shandong
will eventually be linked to the network. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Central Bank Lowers Certificate Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia (BI), the
country's central bank, today once again moved to lower BI
certificate (SBI) interest rates to ease the current monetary
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
BI lowered the one-week SBI interest rate by 1 percentage
point, from 20 percent to 19 percent, while the two-week SBI rate
was lowered 1 percentage point also, from 22 percent to 21
percent.
</P>
<P>
The one-month SBI interest rate was lowered from 27 t0 25
percent, while the three-month SBI interest rate reduced from 25
to 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
For overnight certificates, the interest rate remained at 15
percent, the six months still at 12.125 percent and 12 months at
12.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at the Jakarta Interbank Spot Market by 10:00 a.m.
local time, the rupiah (Indonesian currency) value weakened by 10
points, to 2,900/2,910 per U.S. dollar. Earlier at the opening
session, it stood at 2,890/2,900 per dollar.
</P>
<P>
The central bank raised its one-month and three-month SBI rates
on August 19 in order to stabilize the rupiah against the U.S.
dollar.
</P>
<P>
The new action was a follow-up to the government reform package
announced on September 3 to relax the tight monetary policy in
stages.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has fallen more than 10 percent in the past month
and nearly 23 percent since January this year following offshore
speculative attacks on the currency and a rush by local companies
to hedge their foreign borrowings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0117 </DOCNO>
