<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Coffee Output Estimated to Decline This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- This year's world coffee
production is estimated to decline due to the drought that hit
several coffee-producing nations, an official of the Indonesian
Coffee and Cacao Research Center said today.
</P>
<P>
This year, Brazil is estimated to produce only 25 million bags,
 down from its usual 29 million bags a year, and Colombia, only 10
million bags, down from its usual 18 million bags a year, said
Deputy Director of center Surip Mawardi in Surabaya, East Java,
according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
"Even Indonesia, which usually produces 425,000 tons a year, is
expected to have a lower production," he added.
</P>
<P>
Mawardi said the decline in world production of coffee will
raise its price in the world market. At grower's level, the per kg
price of Robusta Coffee is 3,000 rupiah (about one U.S. dollar)
and Arabica Coffee from 6,000 to 7,000 rupiah (2 to 2.3 dollars),
he said, adding that coffee prices are expected to remain at this
level until the end of the year, after which they are expected to
stabilize.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports said coffee markets in London and New York
came back to a boil this week as the main feature on the
commodities markets, following the summer break, heated up by the
prospect of a low harvest in Indonesia, which is the world's third
largest coffee exporter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
