<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: SADC Working Toward Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLANTYRE, Malawi, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Countries in
southern Africa are working on economic integration through
tightened cooperations in the sub-region and beyond.
</P>
<P>
Economic integration has been the main theme during the
one-day summit of the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) held in Blantyre, southern Malawi Monday.
</P>
<P>
The communique was issued after the 17th summit of the
12-member group admitted the Democratic Republic of Congo and the
Seychelles into the regional body, expanding it to 14.
</P>
<P>
The summit had been fruitful and productive as it adopted two
declarations on gender equality and land-mines and two protocols
on trade and mining, which have combined to show to the world
SADC's courage and efforts for the region's integration for
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
The SADC summit is to find ways to maintain a sustainable
development through tighter economic ties among the member
states.
</P>
<P>
The development of human resources, a topic that has drawn the
attention of the leaders at the SADC summit, is said to be the
key for future prosperity in the region.
</P>
<P>
Gertrude Mongella, chairperson of the United Nations Fourth
World Conference on Women, regarded the summit as an important
"milestone" on the way to democracy and development.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the region, which is rich in mineral resources,
decided in their protocol on mining to harmonize national and
regional policies, strategies and programs related to the
development and exploitation of mineral resources.
</P>
<P>
This would ensure a better tapping of the natural resources
through inter-dependence and integration with a view to enhancing
its competitiveness and increasing the region's share in world
mineral market.
</P>
<P>
SADC leaders also agreed to discuss the tariff reduction and
modalities for tariff structure reform in preparation for a free
trade zone targeted in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Ever since its founding in 1992, SADC has sought to transform
itself into a more dynamic organization that will lead the region
to greater cooperation and economic integration.
</P>
<P>
"Inter-dependence among neighbors and the pressures of a
globalized economy increasingly defined by regional blocs dictate
that we work together as a region," said South African President
Nelson Mandela, chairman of SADC.
</P>
<P>
A preference for democracy and the peaceful resolution of
disputes, commitment to the disciplined management of public
resources, policies designed to encourage the flourishing of
enterprises and far-reaching plans for construction have become
the norm across the region, Mandela noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
