<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: SADC Working Toward Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLANTYRE, Malawi, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The region, with
abundant human and natural resources, the prevailing peace and
stability, has potential for growth with competitiveness,
according to Kaire Mbuende, Executive Secretary of SADC.
</P>
<P>
SADC is doing everything possible to improve its
competitiveness in line with dictates of the globalization
process, Mbuende said.
</P>
<P>
The sub-regional organization will also help its members to
diversify into manufacturing for export rather than relying on
export of raw materials.
</P>
<P>
While stressing the importance of closer cooperation ties
among member states, SADC is also engaged in searching out ways
to coordinate with other economic and political organizations in
Africa and other international organizations, such as the
Organization of African Unity (OAU), the Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa, African Development Bank and
European Union.
</P>
<P>
SADC, which was set up in August 1992, was aimed at promoting
economic integration toward a fully developed common market.
</P>
<P>
The regional grouping has a total population of 150 million
and a combined Gross Domestic Product (GDP) of 170 billion U.S.
Dollars. All 12 SADC member states registered positive growth
rates last year, ranging from two to more than 10 percent. Seven
states recorded growth rates of five percent or higher.
</P>
<P>
Now with the Democratic Republic of Congo and the Seychelles
admitted to the group, and more with tentative interest in
application, SADC members, between them, will inject new blood
into regional development, especially in mining and tourism
sectors.
</P>
<P>
Malawian President Bakili Muluzi urged SADC members to pay
special attention to the improvement of the efficiency and
productivity of the small and medium scale enterprises, the
informal sectors and the small-holder agricultural sector, which
offer real prospects for gains in productivity.
</P>
<P>
The summit's Land-mine Declaration recalled the savagery and
human suffering unleashed on innocent civilians in the region,
where the largest number of explosive anti-personnel mines in the
world seemed to be scattering around, and called for a "land-mine
free" southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Muluzi, host of the SADC summit said at the meeting that
countries of the group should join their efforts in putting an
end to the region's being used as a testing ground for economic
or social experiments originating from rich and distant
countries.
</P>
<P>
SADC countries should, Muluzi said, bear the burden of their
own cherished hope for integration and prosperity while they get
genuine help from the international communities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Maintaining Close Cooperation With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Austin Hu, acting head of the
World Bank's China mission, told Xinhua today that "the World Bank
has built up a mature and close co-operative partnership with
China and such partnership will continue for a long time."
</P>
<P>
China is an important partner of the World Bank and it is ready
to develop its close co-operation with China further, he said.
</P>
<P>
The bank approved financial aid for 184 projects in China by
the end of June, involving nearly 27.97 billion US dollars,
including 9.2 billion US dollars in concessional loans from its
cheap loan arm, the International Development Association.
</P>
<P>
China rejoined the international financial institution in 1980
and now has bank-funded projects in almost all economic sectors,
but mostly in agriculture, poverty reduction, transportation,
energy, health, education, environmental protection, and
industrial development, according to Hu.
</P>
<P>
He commended China for its excellent work in Bank-aided
projects, saying that the success rate for project implementation
is more than 95 percent in China, well above the world average of
around 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank is ready to support modernization in China,
which has been the Bank's largest client since 1993, he said,
noting that "we are confident about the future development of
China and we want to have role to play in China's growth process."
</P>
<P>
The bank is also interested in China's experience in economic
restructuring and development for possible use in other developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the roughly three billion US dollars in annual
lending in the years up to the year 2000, the World Bank will also
provide China with technical assistance, consultation, and
proposals for policy-making, Hu said.
</P>
<P>
"We want to do our part to help the Chinese economy to
intergrate with the rest of world faster and better," he said,
adding that he has been impressed with China's success in
controlling inflation and achieving an economic soft landing.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the World Bank's annual meeting in Hong Kong
indicates that the international financial institution is fully
confident in economic development in Hong Kong and inland China.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
