<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Race Debate Is Still on in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Australian Independent MP
Pauline Hanson said today she had no regrets about the
controversial maiden speech she delivered one year ago tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The speech, in which she warned Australia was in danger of
being swamped by Asians and called for an end to foreign
investment and a cut in immigration intake, sparked a bitter race
debate in Australia and surprised many Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued today, Hanson said she was proud of the
speech and all it had created, describing the past 12 months as a
year of jubilation and trauma.
</P>
<P>
"On September 10, 1996, I proceeded to deliver a speech that
many of my fellow Australians had been waiting a long time to hear
and yet my fellow colleagues cringed," she said.
</P>
<P>
"I would not change one word of it and would again deliver that
same speech with the same pride and determination as then," Hanson
said.
</P>
<P>
Although her speech was dismissed by Australian Immigration
Minister Philip Ruddock as appalling, racist and beyond contempt
later in the week, Hanson became the most reported and
talked-about Australian citizen in the country and some part of
Asia during the past year.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard, who refused to condemn her speech
last September by saying Hanson has the right to speak her mind,
finally said Hanson was wrong on May 8, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister's attack, which was widely seen as belated,
came amid growing criticism of the government's handling of the
race debate and amid fear that negative images created by the
debate would hurt Australia's trade and other interest with
booming Asia.
</P>
<P>
Asia buys about 41 billion U.S. dollars worth of Australian
goods and services each year, around 60 percent of everything
Australia sells to the world.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to the prime minister's prediction that Hanson
phenomenon will be over in three months, both sides of Australian
politics have continued to attack Hanson's politics.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister and Trade Minister Tim Fischer told a
business breakfast in Beijing today that Hanson's views on Asian
immigration were damaging the tourism and education sectors.
</P>
<P>
Asian tourists and students bring hundreds of millions of U.S.
dollars to Australia each year, creating thousands of jobs.
</P>
<P>
The deputy prime minister said the race debate would be causing
concern among families who were "committing to sending their young
sons and daughters to universities in Australia and wondering if
they'll be safe".
</P>
<P>
Hanson had her One Nation Party registered on March 26, 1997,
nearly three months after the prime minister predicted that plans
for Hanson's party would fail.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, there are no signs that Hanson phenomenon will be
over. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
