<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Tightens Emission Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 9 (Xinhua) -- South China's port city
of Guangzhou recently issued a new regulation on motor vehicle
emissions.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou became the first province in China to require
emission control equipment for all motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Random inspections will be conducted and the licenses of
operators of vehicles failing to meet national emission control
standards will be temporarily suspended.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou's compulsory initial emission control regulations
were introduced last year. Over 70 percent of the vehicles
stopped during random inspections have now passed emission tests, up
significantly from the 46 percent passing rate in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The city government also announced a decision to require all
vehicles to use unleaded gas, effective from October 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
