<HEADLINE> International Coordination Needed To Fight Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A multilateral coordinated
mechanism for combating the ever-growing international crime wave
should be set up as soon as possible, Chinese and foreign experts
attending the 19th International Course of Higher Specialization
for Police Forces have suggested.
</P>
<P>
The international seminar closed here today after a week of
discussions among approxiamtely 280 participants from 67 countries
and regions.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Entao, assistant minister of Public Security of China,
delivered a speech at the closing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
He said that each country should attach importance to the
current threat facing public security in the world, which mainly
includes some problems concerning organized crimes such as drug
trafficking, gun-related crime, white-collar crime and illegal
immigration.
</P>
<P>
Both Chinese and overseas Delegates reached a consensus during
the seminar that the trend of technological advances, grouping and
internationalization of crimes poses new challenges to police
work, and police departments in all countries should increase
contacts and learn from each other's successes to set up a
much-needed, coordinated and multilateral approach.
</P>
<P>
Since adopting the reform and opening-up policy in late 1970s,
China has formulated the strategy of comprehensive management of
public security, and ushered in a whole new set of theories and
tactics in the field of public security management, crime
prevention and combating crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
