<HEADLINE> Expanding East China Port Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- China's Jiangsu Province has
built up a port network in coastal areas and along the Yangtze
River, with 10 Grade 1 ports and two Grade 2 ports open to foreign
vessels.
</P>
<P>
They have business ties with 160 overseas ports and contribute
to the development of foreign and domestic trade. There are a
number of development zones with hi-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
The province now has 104 deep berths capable of handling
10,000-ton and above vessels. In 1996, the ports handled 130
million tons of cargo, 25.41 million tons of which were exports,
up 34 percent and 66.1 percent from 1991, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu's container shipments began in 1981, when it handled
only 3,518 TEUs. By 1996, the figure was 475,000 TEUs.
</P>
<P>
The province is building coal, food and edible oil,
petrochemical, and containers ports. Two large coal ports have
been built, one in Lianyungang, and the other in the provincial
capital of Nanjing.
</P>
<P>
The Pukou Coal Port is the largest along the Yangtze River.
</P>
</TEXT>
