<HEADLINE> Panda Gives Birth to Twins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A giant panda living in a
research center here gave birth to twins this morning -- the
second set of panda twins to enter the world in the past 15 days.
</P>
<P>
The panda siblings weighed 130 grams and 125 grams. The elder,
born about 90 minutes before his brother, is the first of the
fourth-generation of pandas kept in a man-made environment.
</P>
<P>
The seven-year-old Yaya, a first-time mother, is one of the
first set of panda twins in the world to be raised successfully in
an artificial environment. Her grandmother, Meimei, has had 11
children, who make up the world's biggest panda family.
</P>
<P>
Giant pandas have difficulty getting pregnant and their babies
often die young. A female giant panda gets pregnant only once a
year, and can give birth to only one to two babies per
pregnancy. She generally only has one baby from her first
pregnancy, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
The Chengdu Giant Panda Breeding and Research Center, covering
an area of 30-plus hectares in southwest China's Sichuan Province,
is the country's only professional center of the kind. It has a
simulated wild ecological environment for pandas.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda, regarded as a "living fossil," is the most
renowned endangered species. It is estimated that there are only
about 1,000 giant pandas living on earth, most of which live in
the mountains around southwest China's Sichuan Basin.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Wants Peaceful Solution to Civil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The military government in
sierra Leone said today it will not allow its border in the
southeast to be used as a springboard to create any instability
to the new government in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State for the East, Captain Eddie Kanneh said in
a press briefing in the capital here, "we want a peaceful
solution to the war with the Kamajors who are attacking us at
Zimmi (near the Liberian border) but they are headstrong."
</P>
<P>
"They should realize by now that they cannot defeat the
conventional and well trained sierra Leone army," Kanneh said.
</P>
<P>
The official who was on consultations with military
specialists in Freetown, blamed the clashes on the border between
government soldiers and the Kamajors or tribal men "on Nigerian
soldiers" in west African peace-keepers known as ECOMOG based at
the Mano River Bridge.
</P>
<P>
"They've given them (Kamajors) arms and ammunition and
training them," Kanneh claimed.
</P>
<P>
According to Kanneh, in a clash between government soldiers
and Kamajors last Sunday, 12 Kamajors were killed along with five
ULIMO-K fighters belonging to defeated Liberian presidential
candidate, Alhaji Kromah.
</P>
<P>
Kromah has previously denied any involvement with the Kamajors
in Sierra Leone although he is reportedly friendly with ousted
president Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Liberia radio reported today that President Charles
Taylor has ordered his security forces "to increase surveillance
on the (Sierra Leone-Liberian) border to halt any cross border
activities."
</P>
<P>
According to the radio, monitored in Freetown, over 100,000
refugees from Sierra Leone were moving toward the border hoping
to enter Liberia.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted Liberia's Information Minister Joe Mulba as
saying, "we are anxious to restore peace in Sierra Leone."
</P>
<P>
"Liberia is calling on all sides in the conflict to return to
the peace table" and find a solution to the impasse, Mulba said.
</P>
</TEXT>
