<HEADLINE> Euro-Mediterranean Meeting to Convene Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Senior government
representatives from 12 Mediterranean countries will join European
Union officials next month to discuss political and security
issues.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, scheduled for October 22 in Brussels, is one of
the follow-up measures in the implementation of the
Euro-Mediterranean Partnership program.
</P>
<P>
The program was approved on November 28, 1995, in Barcelona,
Spain, by the 15-nation EU and the 12 Mediterranean countries:
Algeria, Cyprus, Egypt, Israel, Jordan, Lebanon, Malta, Morocco,
Palestine, Syria, Tunisia and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The program has created a framework for all-round ties between
the EU and Mediterranean countries, and is aimed at promoting
political, economic and social dialogue between the countries.
</P>
<P>
The Barcelona conference, attended by 28 foreign ministers, has
given rise to an assortment of activities among conference
participants from various sectors including politics, economy,
culture, finance, health and social welfare.
</P>
<P>
The second ministerial conference of the Euro-Mediterranean
partnership was held last April in Malta. 
</P>
