<HEADLINE> Recognizing Excellent College Ethics Teachers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Ethics teachers from 98
colleges and universities in 29 provinces, municipalities and
autonmous regions will be recognized for their
outstanding work.
</P>
<P>
They will gather Thursday at the Great Hall of the People in
Beijing at a ceremony held by the State Education Commission (SEC)
and the Propaganda Department of the Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China.
</P>
<P>
"All 101 teachers to be awarded have had outstanding
achievements in teaching, reforms, and scientific research," said
Xi Guangping, a SEC official in charge of social sciences. Most
of them have received provincial, ministry, or university awards,
and 15 have special State Council stipends because of their
contributions.
</P>
<P>
Zhong Jiadong, a professor at Shanghai's Fudan University, was
praised for bringing Deng Xiaoping's theory into the
classroom. Zhang compiled the teaching materials to describe
China's reforms, opening up, and modernization drive and Deng's
personality.
</P>
<P>
The word 'reform' is a requirement for those who want to be
among the 101 winners. The SEC has started reforming the teaching
of ethics, both in content and in style in colleges and
universities.
</P>
<P>
It calls for teacher improvements. A Marxism-Leninism training
school of People's University will have the first group of
teachers in October. China's top universities will ask social
science deans to get further training there.
</P>
<P>
The 3.02 million college students in China have from four to
seven obligatory classes in Marxist theory and ethics during their
two to five years of schooling. Graduate students are also
required to take one or two political science courses.  
</P>
