<HEADLINE> Philippine Bourse Rebounds Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine stock market
today bounced back sharply on declining domestic interest rates,
fading concerns over political instability and a recovering local
currency.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Stock Exchange composite index (Phisix) surged
122.28 points or 5.8 percent, the biggest single-day gain in two
months, to 2228.85.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts said a statement from President Fidel Ramos
Monday somehow appeased investors. Ramos said the 1998 elections
would be held as scheduled and he would not proclaim martial law.
</P>
<P>
Declining interest rates and a recovering Philippine peso also
contributed to today's rally, they said, adding that they doubted
the rally is sustainable.
</P>
<P>
All sub-indices ended on upward side, with the mining sector
and the commercial and industrial sector posting the biggest gains
to reach 3538.8 points (+178.8) and 3124.7 points (+152.2)
respectively.
</P>
<P>
All shares index rose 32.40 points or 4.7 percent to 711.39
points. Volume turnover was 4.7 billion shares, much higher than
Monday's 2.8 billion. Value turnover was heavy at 30.6 billion
pesos (956 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Advances outnumbered declines 127 to 12, while 36 of the 195
traded issues remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the Phisix fell almost 2.8 percent in early trade,
but buying spurred by Ramos' statement nudged the index to 2106.58
points, only 2.64 points lower than Friday's close. 
</P>
</TEXT>
