<HEADLINE> S. Africa Works to Prevent El Nino Disaster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- a committee of five
cabinet ministers has been set up here to formulate a response to
the unpredicatable weather patterns expected in South Africa due
to the El Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
Water Affairs Minister Kader Asmal said today the committee,
chaired by Provincial Affairs Minister Valli Moosa, was formed to
coordinate national disaster management.
</P>
<P>
It would draw together the recommendations of the respective
departments on El Nino and take them to the cabinet, Asmal said.
</P>
<P>
The committee also consists of Agriculture Minister Derek
Hanekom, Welfare Minister Geraldine Fraser-Moleketi and Defense
Minister Joe Modise.
</P>
<P>
El Nino was unpredictable in terms of when its effects might
be felt and so were the effects themselves, which could range
from floods to drought, Asmal said.
</P>
<P>
It was conservatively estimated that the 1982-1983 El Nino
weather patterns had cost South Africa a loss of 5.1 billion U.S.
Dollars. 
</P>
