<HEADLINE> 32 Killed in Tamil Rebel Attack on Chinese Vessel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- At least 32, including five
civilians, were killed and many others injured while eight crew
members were missing this morning in a Tamil rebel attacked on a
Chinese vessel off Pulmoddai coast in Trincomalee District, Sri
Lanka, military sources said.
</P>
<P>
The clashes occurred when Tamil rebels staged an attack around
1:00 a.m. on the Panama-registered civil cargo ship "MV
Cordiality", owned by China Ocean Shipping Company, at anchor off
Pulmoddai, about 280 kilometers northeast to the capital of
Colombo.
</P>
<P>
31 Chinese crew members and 60 Sri Lankan workers were on board
the ship to load ilmenite sands when the ship was attacked.
</P>
<P>
The engine room of the ship caught fire after the Tamil rebels
fired several rounds of rocket-propelled grenades to the cargo,
which was severely damaged.
</P>
<P>
Government troops who escorted the ship engaged the rebels and
rescued 23 Chinese crew members, including five who jumped into
the sea to escape the attack. The other eight members were
missing.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources in Colombo said those missing could
probably be taken away by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Five Sri Lankan workers were killed by the rebels and another
five were injured.
</P>
<P>
A military spokesman put the death toll of the attackers at 25.
He added that a large number of the rebels were wounded. The army
also suffered two death and four injuries.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan navy sent fast attack craft and boats to assist the
army during the fire exchange. At least four rebel boats were sunk
and another three damaged.
</P>
<P>
On July 8, the rebels hijacked a vessel of the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea hired by the Sri Lankan government to
transport goods to the Jaffna Peninsula when it was on way to
Colombo from the north. 
</P>
</TEXT>
