<HEADLINE> Asia's Leading Aircraft Engine Service Center Opens in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Asia's largest aircraft
engine testing center was launched in Hong Kong, with the
potential to become the region's technical troubleshooter, today's
South China Morning Post reported.
</P>
<P>
Some 600 people will be employed at the center of Hong Kong
Aero Engine Services Ltd. (Haesl), a joint venture between
Rolls-Royce and Hong Kong Aircraft Engineering Co.
</P>
<P>
The plant will test and service Rolls-Royce engines used in the
fleets of Hong Kong flag carriers Cathay Pacific and Dragonair, as
well as the Chinese mainland's airlines, and contracts are being
negotiated around the world.
</P>
<P>
Haesl Director and General Manager Tom Begley said the plant
could become a regional facility, not only performing scheduled
overhauls, but also for trouble-shooting.
</P>
<P>
"This will be one of the leading engine overhaul centers in the
world and we will have the expertise to take that trouble-shooting
role or deal with teething problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will service engines here or send people to deal with
problems while the engine is still on the aircraft."
</P>
<P>
It is expected to take three or four years for the center,
which when completed will cover over 12,000 square meters, to
build up business until it can handle its maximum of 300 engines a
year.  
</P>
