<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Santer Calls Delay in Euro Launch "Unimaginable" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- European Commission President
Jacques Santer has called for a punctual adoption of the single
European currency euro in 1999.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Deutschlandradio Berlin, he said a
delay in its launch was "unimaginable."
</P>
<P>
Santer sharply criticized the recent debates in Germany about a
possible delay of the euro.
</P>
<P>
"The German debate is not appropriate for the entire project of
the European Monetary Union," he said, adding that such a debate
would stir up fears and uncertainty about the fate of the euro.
</P>
<P>
He added that a delay in the launch of the euro needs a change
of the Maastricht Treaty, which would be "unimaginable."
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that German Finance Minister Theo
Waigel would make all efforts to meet the fiscal criteria required
for adopting the euro.
</P>
<P>
Santer also said the current performance by EU nations to meet
the euro convergence criteria had allowed him to be confident that
the euro would be introduced at the scheduled startup date of
January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Germany has stirred up controversies in European capitals
recently when Hans Tietmeyer, president of Germany's central bank,
said in a newspaper interview that a delay of the euro would not
be "a disaster."
</P>
<P>
Kurt Biedenkopf, premier of the German state of Saxony, made a
concrete call Monday for a five-year delay in the euro launch.
</P>
<P>
The debates came amid rising doubts over whether key EU
countries, including Germany and France, would be able to meet the
fiscal criteria this year to qualify for the euro.
</P>
<P>
Under the Maastricht Treaty, countries wishing to join the euro
club are required, among other criteria, to keep their budget
deficit under three percent of GDP and overall national debt below
60 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
The first wave of countries to join the European Monetary Union
will be chosen in the spring of 1998, based on full economic data
of the EU member states in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
