<HEADLINE> S. Africa's National Party Gets New Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's opposition
National Party Executive Director Marthinus Van Schalkwyk has been
elected party chief to replace F. W. De Klerk.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made to a crowd of cheering National Party
supporters today after a meeting a 105-member electoral college.
</P>
<P>
Schalkwyk, 37, has become the party's eighth leader since its
inception in 1914. He is due to address a press conference later
today.
</P>
<P>
Schalkwyk said earlier that he favored "coalition government" for
South Africa, and that former National Party General Secretary Roelf
Meyer was welcome to return to the party -- under his leadership.
</P>
<P>
"Political parties must work together and i foresee that the
National Party will be part of a coalition government in 2004,"
Schalkwyk said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
The National Party withdrwed from the government of
national unity last year due to its sharp political differences with
the ruling African National Congress.
</P>
<P>
Former South African President De Klerk, who declared retirment on
August 26, will make his farewell address to parliament later today.
His resignation as an member of parliament is expected to come into
effect this month.
</P>
<P>
De Klerk said his decision to quit the leadership and leave
active politics would make way for a new leader to take the party
into the 1999 general elections. 
</P>
