<HEADLINE> Party Congress Delegates Arrive in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Delegates attending the 15th
National Congress of the Communist Party of China (CPC), which is
to open on September 12, began arriving in Beijing today at the
railway station and Capital Airport.
</P>
<P>
The new arrivals told Xinhua that they have high hopes for the
party congress. Wang Enmao, an 84-year-old revolutionary veteran
who has held the post of party secretary of the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region for a long time, is a special delegate directly
invited by the CPC Central Committee. This eye-witness to the
twists and turns of several decades of change says he hopes the
party congress can speed up development in the final years of the
century.
</P>
<P>
Memet, head of Xinjiang's Turpan Prefecture, said that
representing the 540,000 people of different ethnic groups and
20,000 party members in his autonomous region is a great and
glorious task. "At this turning point of the century, a critical
moment in the country's reform and opening-up drive, the congress
has a historic significance," he said.
</P>
<P>
Li Peishu of Guizhou province, southwest China, said that the
people expect China's current state policy to remain unchanged. As
a delegate, he firmly believes that the CPC's basic line is good
for China's development and cannot be changed.
</P>
<P>
A major item on the agenda is the choice of a new CPC central
committee. Hu Kehui, a Guizhou delegate, said that she will use
the right entrusted her by the Party Constitution to choose a new
central leading group "who can lead the country to the new
century."
</P>
<P>
Other delegates are concerned about the reform of large and
medium-sized state-owned enterprises. Liu Yiming, an industrial
worker from the Harbin Steam Turbine Co. Ltd. in the capital of
the northermost Heilongjiang province, held that the congress
could provide a more favorable environment for reforming and
developing state-owned firms.
</P>
<P>
Other delegates praise the achievements of the past five years,
following the 14th Party Congress, and expressed the hope that the
congress could help enterprise reforms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
