<HEADLINE> Drought in Uganda Might Cause Food Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Current dry season in Uganda
is predicted to end in mid-September, a senior official was
quoted as saying by a local paper today.
</P>
<P>
Gerald Sendaula, the minister of natural resources, told The
New Vision that the coming rain season, characterized by heavy
rains countrywide, will run till the end of this year or the
beginning of the next year.
</P>
<P>
A previous report from the board of meteorology said the
coming rain season will start at the beginning of this month.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has two dry seasons, one from late November to February
and the other is from June to July. But the previous dry season
was prolonged from late last November to March 25 this year.
</P>
<P>
The change in rainfall pattern is caused by El-Nino, the
surface warming of equatorial Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
Persistent drought in the east have aroused worry among
people. A report from Kapchorwa district in the region said some
officials in the district imposed a road toll on the businessmen
sending out food. The region will suffer from lack of enough
food, they warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
