<HEADLINE> Pakistan Awaits Positive Response from India for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Secretary
Shamshad Ahmed said today that he would certainly wish to visit
India this month to resume the third round of Pakistan-India
foreign secretary-level talks.
</P>
<P>
"But it depends on India's response and its sincerity in
resolving outstanding issues between the two countries," Shamshad
told the official Associated Press of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is ready to talk with India for positive outcome and
hopes that India will reciprocate in the same manner, said
Shamshad.
</P>
<P>
He said that Pakistan wants "to reverse the tide of hostilities
with India for the peace and socio-economic development of each
other".
</P>
<P>
He dispelled the impression that there was hesitation on the
part of Pakistan for resuming the talks, which was agreed upon at
the end of the second round of talks in Islamabad in June.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question, Shamshad confirmed that Pakistan had
received a set of dates for the talks from India, proposing the
talks in the middle of this month.
</P>
<P>
"We are examining the dates and waiting for explanation," said
Shamshad, adding that Pakistan sought from India about the
commitment which was made at the end of the second round of talks.
</P>
<P>
There was understanding between the two countries that a
mechanism would be evolved for resolving the outstanding issues,
including the core issue of Kashmir, he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan desired peace in the region, and both Pakistan and
India should concentrate on the socio-economic development of
their people, said Shamshad.
</P>
<P>
Stressing Pakistan's keen desire for dialogue with India,
Shamshad said that it should be meaningful and constructive.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the Kashmir issue should be settled in
accordance with the wishes of the people of Kashmir and the
relevant resolutions of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India resumed their foreign secretary-level talks
in March this year after a hiatus of more than three years. The
talks had broken down in January 1994 due to their differences
over the issue of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The two countries held their second round of foreign
secretary-level talks in Islamabad in June this year. At the end
of the talks the two sides agreed that the third round of talks
would be held in New Delhi this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
