<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Calls for Simplified Agriculture Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A European Union (EU)
official today urged the simplification of the EU agricultural
policy to overcome the contradictions and overlaps existing
between its agricultural schemes and programs.
</P>
<P>
The EU must correct the situation if it wants to get support
from farmers and the rest of the society for its common
agricultural policy (CAP), Franz Fischler, EU Commissioner for
Agriculture and Rural Development, said at a three-day informal
meeting of EU agriculture ministers which started Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The EU needed to encourage structural adjustment and multiple
function in agriculture in order to continue to provide a high
quality of life to its citizens, the commissioner said.
</P>
<P>
He also called for a continued CAP reform, which the EU started
in 1992, in order to make the EU's agriculture sector "fit for the
years to come."
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the CAP must not only be able to cope with
different market management problems, but also to meet the
expectations of society as a whole.
</P>
<P>
"If the Union were to decide under these circumstances to leave
the present CAP in place, we would have to prepare ourselves to
live with a significant gap between internal and international
prices over the longer term," the commissioner said.
</P>
<P>
He explained that experts foresaw stasis on the EU's internal
markets but a long-term positive outlook on non-EU markets, adding
that the EU could count on the high but stable prices on most
world markets.
</P>
<P>
Farm incomes across the EU have grown on average at an annual
rate of 4.5 percent and farmers have adjusted to the new
conditions since the 1992 reform, according to the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that there still remained considerable
income disparities between individual member states and regions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
