<HEADLINE> Sudanese Refugee Camps in Uganda Closed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 9 (Xinhau) -- The Uganda Red Cross Society
has closed all Sudanese refugee camps in Koboko and Arua
districts in northwestern Uganda, reported the local media today.
</P>
<P>
The camps which had sheltered Sudanese refugees were closed
down last week following an xodus of over 26,000 refugees back to
southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The refugees had fled from fierce fighting between the rebel
Sudanese People's Liberation Army led by John Garang and the
government troops since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The closing of the camps is due to the return of the refugees
to southern Sudan follows relative calm now prevailing there, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Garang said recently that his army has captured most part of
southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
There were 184,000 Sudanese refugees in northern Uganda in
February 1994. Since then many of them have returned back home
due to relative calm prevailing in southern sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
