<HEADLINE> Redevelopment Planned for HK Downtown Office Tower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Hongkong Land has announced
a 2.3-billion-HK-dollar (295 million U.S. dollars) redevelopment
scheme to replace an old block in Central, the Hong Kong Island,
with a state-of-the-art office tower, the local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Work on the building, provisionally renamed as 11 Chater Road,
is expected to start in October next year and be completed in
2003. Bank loans will be used to fund the project.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director Percy Weatherall told reporters that the time
is right for Hongkong Land to maximize the value of its oldest
property in Hong Kong. Concern is growing, analysts said, that the
35-year-old Swire House will lose tenants to more modern
developments with better facilities.
</P>
<P>
"The building will be a new flagship for the Hongkong Land core
portfolio," said Weatherall.
</P>
<P>
The new 30-story office tower, with the latest facilities, will
be able to accommodate the high specifications of multinational
banking and financial sector tenants, he said.
</P>
<P>
It will be constructed above a three-level podium and a
three-level basement. New pedestrian bridges will join the
building to other Hongkong Land properties in Central.
</P>
<P>
Hongkong Land, part of the British conglomerate Jardine, owns
some 40 percent of the office space in the business district,
including Swire House, Jardine House, Exchange Square, the Princes
Building and the Hong Kong Club Building.  
</P>
</TEXT>
