<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zairean criminals in S. Africa Wanted by DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG,September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic Republic
of Congo (DRC) has cancelled all former Zairean diplomatic and
official passports and began a manhunt for military and civilian
"criminals" now living in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The provisional list released by the DRC embassy in Pretoria
includes the names of five generals and four colonels,as well as
11 civilians who formerly occupied high-ranking posts in the
Mobutu government, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
"The faithful criminals were now refugees in South Africa,"
the embassy said in a statement, adding it had suggested to all
foreign embassies based in South Africa not to grant visas to
anyone who held a passport of "Republic of Zaire".
</P>
<P>
The statement claimed that the criminals become refugees in
South Africa "with huge fortunes stolen from public treasury in
Zaire and with this money they are "initiating actions to create
civil war in the DRC".
</P>
<P>
During his official visit to South Africa last month, DRC
President Laurent Kabila appealed to President Nelson Mandela to
expel the generals living in Johannesburg and Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
The generals being sought include Baramoto, Mobutu's Commander
of National Police who allegedly killed several politicians.
</P>
<P>
Civilian "criminals" include Ngbanda Atumba, former Special
Intelligence Adviser, allegedly responsible for the murder of
several kindnapped Congolese citizens. He is said to possess
millions of U.S.Dollars stolen from public coffers.
</P>
<P>
Mandela told Kabila last month that a special South African
working team has been established for the investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
