<HEADLINE> S.African Vice-President to Visit Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- South African Vice-President
Thambo Mbeki will pay a two-day working visit to Nigeria next
week, the Vanguard newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
During his visit from September 17 to 18, Mbeki is expected to
deliver a special message from President Nelson Mandela to
Nigerian Head of State Sani Abacha, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources here were quoted as saying that Mbeki's
visit is part of the current diplomatic moves at thawing recent
frosty relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two leading African countries fell to an
all-time low in late 1995, when S. Africa led the campaign in the
Commonwealth that suspended Nigeria's membership for executing
Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other Ogoni activists.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Foreign Ministry Chief Tom Ikimi visited S. Africa
last week, during which he delivered a special message from
Abacha to President Mandela.
</P>
<P>
The visit helped seal a deal between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
S. Africa has reportedly agreed not to oppose Nigeria "in any
way" at the October Commonwealth Summit in Edinburgh, Scotland,
which will take the final decision on Nigeria's membership.
</P>
<P>
S. Africa also agreed to co-operate with Nigeria-led ECOWAS
(the Economic Community of West African States) in its effort to
restore the legitimate government of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah
in Sierra Leone.  
</P>
</TEXT>
