<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Airways Threatened with Strike Notice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Kenya Airways, which saw its
pre-tax profit down by 31 percent to one billion Shillings (about
US$18.5 million) in the year ending on March 31, 1997, is now
facing a new strike notice issued by a trade union.
</P>
<P>
The Transport and Allied Workers Union (TAWU) announced last
week it would launch a strike unless the airlines withdraws its
threat to sack 15 shop stewards who are active in the union, the
Kenya Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The TAWU issued a strike notice in July to seek improved
conditions of service for the unionizable staff of the national
carrier but then called it off after the Ministry of Labor
advised the two sides to seek out of court arbitration.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the company has made no formal response to the
fresh strike notice.
</P>
<P>
Net profit of the company fell from 1.4 billion Shillings
(approximately US$25.5 million) in 1995/96 to 851.6 million
Shillings (US$15 million) in the just-ended fiscal year, said the
firm's annual report for 1997.
</P>
<P>
The company attributes the profit decline to higher worldwide
fuel prices, the hefty pay increase and foreign exchange losses
caused by the strength of the Shilling.
</P>
<P>
Income from passenger tickets increased by 10 percent in the
year, while total income reached 10.7 billion Shillings (about
194 million US Dollars), 6.6 percent higher than in 1995/1996.
</P>
<P>
However, this increase is insufficient to compensate for the
company's rising costs, which grew 10.1 percent over the previous
year, the airlines said in the report.
</P>
<P>
Higher oil prices worldwide resulted in additional aviation
fuel costs of 250 million Shillings (about 4.5 million US
Dollars) and labor costs increased by 27 percent during the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
