<HEADLINE> Cape Town to Continue Infrastructure Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The South African
central government will proceed with its 370-million U.S. Dollar
infrastructure plan for western Cape Province despite Cape Town's
failure to host the 2004 Olympic Games, local daily Business Day
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The infrastructure plan included 18 million U.S. Dollars,
which had been set aside for sports facilities, Mbali Swana,
director of project management with the Olympic Bid Company, told
reporters in Cape Town, capital of western Cape Province.
</P>
<P>
The projects, which included the upgrade of Cape Town
International Airport, railway stations and some important public
facilities, would proceed "because they are in accordance with
the central government's development objective", Swana said.
</P>
<P>
Sport facilities such as badminton courts and judo, boxing and
softball halls would be handed over to local communities early
next year.
</P>
<P>
The projects were in line with government plans to boost
emerging black contractors, and to give disadvantaged communities
access to sports facilities, said Swana. 
</P>
