<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Indonesia Successful in Reducing Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- International recognition of
Indonesia's success in reducing poverty made President Soeharto
the world's first head of state to receive a special citation from
the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) for the country's
extraordinary achievements in alleviating poverty.
</P>
<P>
In awarding the citation to Soeharto Monday here, UNDP
Administrator James Gustave Speth said: "The award is a
recognition of Soeharto's and Indonesia's outstanding
accomplishment and commitment to significant reduction and
continued eradication of poverty."
</P>
<P>
The success of Indonesia's poverty eradication drive is
regarded as one of the results of the country's first 25-year
long-term development plan which ended in 1994.
</P>
<P>
By applying the development trilogy -- high economic growth,
equal distribution of development and stability, the government
consistently used economic growth to contribute to poverty
reduction through the creation of jobs.
</P>
<P>
But the government at the same time also remained quite aware
that economic growth is not a panacea for poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
Due to a sustained growth of around seven percent a year for
the last three decades, Indonesia, one of the world's poorest
nations in the 1960s, successfully brought poverty down to 11
percent of its population from 60 percent in 1970.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the development drive also increased life expectancy
by almost 50 percent and per capita income from 50 U.S. dollars to
1,000 dollars, while it also cut the illiteracy rate by two
thirds.
</P>
<P>
Economic experts held that those were not easy tasks as
Indonesia has a large population, now around 200 million. And
almost 60 percent of the population live on Java Island which has
only seven percent of the land area in the country. The rest of
the population is scattered on dozens of large islands as well as
about 3,000 populated islands in the archipelago.
</P>
<P>
State Minister for National Development Planning Ginandjar
Kartasasmita said Monday at a regional workshop on comparative
experiences in poverty eradication that rapid economic growth has
improved Indonesia's capability to address poverty problems.
</P>
<P>
On the experience in poverty eradication, the minister said the
Indonesian government from the very beginning had put agriculture
on the first priority as some 80 percent of its population live in
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
By building dams, providing roads and electricity, the rural
economy was opened up. And the first target achieved after several
years of hard work was rice self-sufficiency in 1984. In the
process, rural areas were transformed from economically dormant
into productive and vibrant parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
With the development of the rural economy, a substantial amount
of public investment has been directed to the improvement of the
education and health condition of the people. The first priority
was to achieve six-year universal primary education and the target
now is moving to nine-year universal education.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, Indonesia now has 170,000
primary schools, which accommodate around 30 million pupils.
</P>
<P>
Education is a driving force behind women's emancipation in
Indonesia. Community health services, eradication of communicable
diseases and improvement of nutritional standards of the people
are the basic components of health development.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are 7,000 community health centers and 21,000
auxiliary centers scattered all over the country.
</P>
<P>
The containment of population is another element for the
economic development and poverty eradication. The government has
been able to reduce population growth from 2.4 percent per year in
the 1970s to 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government also emphasized job creation in its
development program. In the past 25 years, it created 42.5 million
new jobs.
</P>
<P>
The government held that poor people are poor because their
access to productive assets is limited, especially their access to
capital. So, the central and local governments have made joint
efforts to develop financial schemes to help poor people gain
access to capital, for instance, through the banking system to
create various schemes that provide small-scale credits.
</P>
<P>
All commercial banks operating in Indonesia have been requested
to provide at least 22 percent of their overall credit to
cooperatives and small-scale businesses. Various grass-roots
financial institutions were established to channel micro credit to
the people.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994 when the country entered the second long-term
development plan, the Indonesian government has taken many
measures to eradicate poverty including providing funds to poor
people living in the poorest villages through family welfare
saving program.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government has determined to eradicate poverty
in absolute terms during the second long-term development plan. By
the year 2005, the poverty level will have been reduced to less
than 3.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
