<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Have Second National Phone Carrier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will select its second
national telecommunications network carrier next month through
competitive bidding, the Punch newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Communications Minister Tajudeen Olanrewaju said that the idea has
been approved by the federal government and that the second carrier
would provide long distance and international services.
</P>
<P>
Hitherto such services have been monopolized by the Nigerian
Telecommunications (NITEL). Though some private companies have been
admitted into the sector, their businesses are restricted to certain
fields.
</P>
<P>
The minister disclosed that the internal process and in-house
procedures for the selection of the second carrier have been finished.
</P>
<P>
He added that the tender for bids would be advertised in both local
and foreign media to ensure openess in the selection.
</P>
<P>
In another development, a private firm, Motophone Nigeria Limited
has been authorized to provide VSAT (Very Small Aperture Terminal) Hub
and international service, breaking another monopoly of the NITEL.
</P>
<P>
Before this, a number of firms have been licensed to provide
domestic VSAT service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
