<HEADLINE> Agricultural Mechanization Urged in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian agricultural mechanization
expert Joseph Sunday Adeoti has urged the country to establish its own
farm machine manufacturing industry, the Punch newspaper reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Adeoti made the call on Monday at the National Center for
Development for Agricultural Mechanization in Ilorin, Kwara State.
</P>
<P>
"Nigeria is blessed with an area of 98.3 million hectares, out of
which 72 percent is considered as suitable for agriculture, less than
30 percent is currently under-cultivated," he said.
</P>
<P>
Adeoti pointed out that Nigeria can attain appreciable level of
self-sufficiency in food production, if it strives to achieve "a
target of about 25 percent mechanization on farms in the next decade".
</P>
<P>
He estimated that the country would require at least 65 billion
Naira (about 79 million U.S. dollars) on agricultural machinery for
field operations in the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
"The establishment of effective local agricultural machinery
manufacturing industry is a prerequisite for viable agriculture
industry anywhere," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
