<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Calls for Simplified Agriculture Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LUXEMBOURG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A European Union (EU)
official here today urged to simplify the EU's agricultural policy
in order to overcome the contradictions and overlaps existing
between its different agricultural schemes and programs.
</P>
<P>
The EU must rectify the situation if it wants to get support
from farmers and the rest of the society for its common agricultural
policy (CAP), Franz Fischler, EU commissioner for agriculture and
rural development, said at an informal meeting of EU agriculture
ministers here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The EU needed to encourage structural adjustment and multiple
function in agriculture in order to continue to provide a high
quality of life to its citizens, the commissioner told the
three-day meeting which started Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He also called for a continued CAP reform, which the EU started
in 1992, in order to make the EU's agriculture sector "fit for the
years to come".
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the CAP must not only be able to cope with
different market management problems, but also meet the expectations
of society as a whole.
</P>
<P>
"If the Union were to decide under these circumstances to leave
the present CAP in place, we would have to prepare ourselves to live
with a significant gap between internal and international prices
over the longer term," the commissioner said.
</P>
<P>
He explained that experts foresaw stasis on the EU's internal
markets but a long-term positive outlook on non-EU markets, adding
that the EU could count on the high but stable prices on most world
markets.
</P>
<P>
Farm incomes across the EU have grown on average by 4.5 percent
a year and farmers have adjusted to the new conditions since the
1992 reform, according to the EU agriculture commissioner.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that there still remained considerable
income disparities between individual member states and regions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
