<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Modern Bread-Basket in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Beidahuang, in China's
Heilongjiang province, has become an important base of marketable
grain, with five billion kg in annual output of commodity grain.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 50 years, it has produced 95.8 billion kg of
grain and beans, of which 65.65 billion kg were sold to the
state. Its farms have netted the state 5.95 billion yuan in taxes
and profits.
</P>
<P>
The government-backed cultivation programs in an area known for
its wasteland and marshes started in 1947. But the first
large-scale cultivation started in the 1950s when General Wang
Zhen led 100,000 ex-soldiers in setting up state-owned farms.
</P>
<P>
In the past half century, 700,000 young people, including
140,000 ex-soldiers and 50,000 university grads, were settled in
Beidahuang, which means 'huge wasteland in the north'.
</P>
<P>
There are now 103 Heilongjiang General Agricultural Cultivation
Bureau farms, with nearly 2,000 support firms in the transport and
service sectors, and a population of 1.57 million, 635,000 of whom
are farm workers.
</P>
<P>
The farms have made a great effort at mechanization in the past
several decades, and now have 50,000 tractors, combines, diggers,
and trucks, and 24 airplanes for farm use.
</P>
<P>
A research and service system has been formed for cultivation,
with 17 research institutes, nine technology promotion centers,
and 103 technology promotion stations, with more than 100,000
agronomists and technicians.
</P>
<P>
There are 140 small towns taking shape on the former wasteland
and residents now receive TV shows and have good
telecommunications at home.
</P>
<P>
Nine-year compulsory education has also been adopted for local
schoolchildren. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Santer Says Euro Delay "Unimaginable" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- European Commission President Jacques
Santer has once again called for a punctual start of the planned
single European currency, the Euro, saying that a delay in its 1999
launch was "unimaginable", German media reported today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Deutschlandradio Berlin on Tuesday, Santer
voiced sharp criticism over recent debates in Germany about a possible
delay of the Euro.
</P>
<P>
"The German debate is not appropriate for the entire project of the
European Monetary Union," he said, adding that such a debate would
stir up fears and uncertainty about the future of the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, a delay in the launch of the Euro needs a change in the
EU Maastricht treaty, which was "unimaginable", Santer added.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
would make all efforts to meet the fiscal criteria required for
qualifying for the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Santer also noted that the current performance by EU nations to
meet the Euro convergence criteria had allowed him to be confident
that the Euro would be introduced at the scheduled startup date of
January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Germany has stirred up controversies in European capitals recently
when Hans Tietmeyer, president of Germany's central bank, said in a
newspaper interview that a delay of the Euro would not be "a
disaster".
</P>
<P>
On top of that, Kurt Biedenkopf, premier of the German state of
Saxony, on Monday also made a concrete call for a five-year delay for
the Euro launch.
</P>
<P>
The debates came amid rising doubts over whether key countries in
the E.U., including Germany and France, would be able to meet the
fiscal criteria this year to qualify for the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Under the Maastricht treaty, countries wishing to join the Euro
club are required, among other things, to bring their budget deficit
to less than 3 percent and overall national debt to below 60
percent of the gross domestic product. The first wave of countries to
join the Monetary Union will be chosen in the spring of 1998, based on
EU states' full economic data in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
