<HEADLINE> 1,550 HK Policemen to Take Charge of Security for WB Meetings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- About 1,550 police officers
will be directly involved in the security operation for the 1997
World Bank Group and International Monetary Fund (WB/IMF) Annual
Meetings and associated seminars to be held here between September
15 and 25.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong Police have the overall responsibility of security
arrangements for the function which will be held at the Hong Kong
Convention and Exhibition Center (HKCEC), and the protection of
any visiting dignitaries," Chief Superintendent (Special Duties)
of Operations Wing Tang King-shing said today.
</P>
<P>
"Within the meeting venues, the Hong Kong Monetary Authority
has contracted a private company to provide security service," he
told a joint press conference given by the Police Planning and
Implementation Team and Transport Department.
</P>
<P>
Starting from September 12, the newly-built HKCEC Extension and
the surrounding roads will be secured with a full defensive
search and tight access control. Only accredited participants,
staff and press representatives with a security pass will be
allowed access.
</P>
<P>
Special equipment such as water-filled barriers, metal
detector archways, X-ray machines and explosive detectors would
be used to assist in the operation, he added. 
</P>
