<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 09:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Approves 1998 Budget Cuts Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli Cabinet today
approved a plan for the 1998 budget characterized by a wide range
of fund cuts proposed by the Ministry of Finance, the state-run
Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The budget plan was approved by a 11-6 vote after more than 16
hours of a marathon debate Monday night, with one minister
abstaining. The cuts amounted to 2.3 billion shekels (about 660
million U.S. dollars) including 400 million shekels (114 million
dollars) from the military.
</P>
<P>
The budget proposed by Finance Minister Ya'acov Neeman totals
195 billion shekels (55 billion dollars). With those cuts, the
minister manages to meet the strategy of keeping the 1998 budget
deficit no higher than 2.4 percent of the gross domestic product
(GNP).
</P>
<P>
The proposal was made because tax revenues are lagging behind
earlier forecasts as a result of the dramatic slowdown of Israel's
economy, Finance Ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, the defense budget was cut from 550
million shekels (142 million dollars) to 400 million shekels (114
million dollars). This means reduced Israeli army representatives
soldier's academic studies.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai had hoped to increase his
budget by some 10 million dollars to renew weapons and ammunition
supplies.
</P>
<P>
The Education Ministry' budget was also cut by 250 million
shekels (71 million dollars). However, the ministry was allowed to
decide where the cuts are made, and there will be obvious cuts in
the number of school hours.
</P>
<P>
The health service was deeply affected by the budget cuts. The
cuts plan gave greater financial independence to health funds,
which in turn will ask the public for additional funding.
</P>
<P>
Israel's rapid economic expansion over the past five years has
now slowed down, with the growth rate this year being projected at
only 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu risks political danger in
slashing the budget, for a failure to have that budget passed by
the parliament will possibly bring down his government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
