<HEADLINE> Communique of Seventh Plenum of 14th CPC Central Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Following is the full text of
the Communique of the Seventh Plenary Session of the 14th Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China(CPC):
</P>
<P>
The Seventh Plenum of the 14th CPC Central Committee was held
in Beijing from September 6 through 9 of 1997.
</P>
<P>
A total of 182 members and 123 alternate members of the CPC
Central Committee attended the plenum, with members of the CPC
Central Commission for Discipline Inspection and leading officials
of the departments concerned attending as non-voting members.
</P>
<P>
The Plenum was presided over by the Political Bureau of the CPC
Central Committee. Comrade Jiang Zemin, general secretary of the
CPC Central Committee, delivered an important speech.
</P>
<P>
It was decided at the plenum that the 15th National Congress of
the Chinese Communist Party will open in Beijing on September 12.
</P>
<P>
The Plenum discussed and approved the report which will be
presented by the Central Committee to the 15th National Congress
of the Party. "An Amendment to the Constitution of the Communist
Party of China" was also discussed and approved at the Plenum.
The two documents will be submitted to the 15 National Congress
of the Party for discussions, the plenum unanimously decided.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the stipulations of the Party Constitution,
the plenum decided to make Keyun Bawudun a full member of the CPC
Central Committee from alternate membership.
</P>
<P>
The plenum discussed and approved the investigation report of
the CPC Central Commission for Discipline Inspection about the
case of Chen Xitong.
</P>
<P>
In an atmosphere of democracy and solidarity, the plenum had a
warm discussion on a number of key issues concerning China's
reform and opening-up and trans-century development of the
socialist modernization construction and full preparations have
been made for the victorious convening of the 15th National Party
Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
