<HEADLINE> German Inflation Rate Rises to 31-Month High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Germany's inflation rose in August to
its highest level since January 1995, creeping up to an annual rate of
2.1 percent from July's 1.9 percent, the German Federal Statistics
Office said today.
</P>
<P>
When calculated on a month-on-month basis, Germany's consumer
prices edged up just 0.1 percent in August, after a 0.5 percent rise
in July.
</P>
<P>
While the western half of the country saw prices up 0.2 percent
from July, those in eastern Germany dropped by 0.1 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
Despite the overall price hike, Germany's central bank on Tuesday
still decided to leave one of its key interest rate, the securities
repurchase rate, unchanged at 3.0 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
