<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Take-Off in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region has reached a turning point in its
economic development with its improved infrastructure, thanks to
the country's strategy of developing western regions and their
natural resources.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang has 129 kinds of minerals and large reserves of 76 of
them. The central and regional governments have spent nearly 50
billion yuan on oilfields there, to enlarge its capability of
producing 17 million tons of crude oil annually.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Xinjiang produced 14.5 million tons of crude and more
than 31 billion yuan worth of petrochemical products that
accounted for 46 percent of the region's industrial output value.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang has become the country's largest cotton grower and a
major grain producer. In the past five years, the region produced
over 4.1 million tons of cotton.
</P>
<P>
It now ranks 14th in the country in cotton textile production
and 7th in woolen textiles. The country is moving textile
production from eastern, coastal areas to the west and Xinjiang
and plans to use this to become one of the country's top textile
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
It also has six industrial bases for sugar, fur and leather
goods, hops, and salt, and as a border region, it has mapped out
preferential policies for foreign investment. By the end of June,
the region had trade ties with 68 foreign countries and regions,
and absorbed nearly 1.8 billion US dollars in foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 of its enterprises have export and import
licenses and 14 land-ports have been opened for foreign
trade. Last year, exports and imports were more than 1.4 billion
US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang has opened 50 domestic and international air routes
from its airports.
</P>
<P>
There are 15 satellite telecoms ground stations and several
fiber telecommunications lines.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, its economy has grown at 10 percent annually. Its
GDP grew from 33.6 billion yuan in 1991, to 91.2 billion yuan in
1996, while per-capita GDP also went from 1,100 yuan to over 5,100
yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
