<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Railway Taxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- It's not easy to find a train
that stops for someone who is standing alongside the tracks waving
his or her hand as if he or she were flagging a taxi down.
</P>
<P>
But people in a remote part of China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region can do just that. The local railway
administration recently began this "railway taxi" on a 126-seat
train with three crewmen: an engineer, an attendant, and a
policeman.
</P>
<P>
"The train provides a lot of convenience," said one local
Mongolian woman named Gaowa. "In the past, it took a long time and
a lot of trouble just to go and see my parents," she said.
</P>
<P>
The idea of operating a passenger train that could be flagged
down on a 130 km-section of railway came from complaints by many
residents, mainly farmers and herdsmen, about the immense
inconvenience of travel in the area. It passes through 20 villages
and has eight regular stops as well.
</P>
<P>
Its began operation on July 5 and has carried over 9,000
passengers, bringing in nearly 70,000 yuan in revenues.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts say that this may not be a very popular move for
the railways as a whole, but that it shows that the railway
administration is sincere. Railways have long been regarded the
big brother of transport services, and the railway administration
has been paying great attention to improve its service in recent
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands Migrate From Key Power Station Area (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Fan Youqiong's happiness was
apparent as she stood in front of her family's new house, a
beautiful two-storey building with floor space of more than 100
square meters.
</P>
<P>
"I was short of money and simply prepared to refurbish our old
ramshackled home," Fan said.
</P>
<P>
The 42-year-old female farmer moved to her new home from
Yanbian County, Panzhihua City, in southwest China's Sichuan
Province. The Ertan Hydropower Station, the largest facility of
its kind to be completed this century, will lead to the inundation
of her home village so her family was one of 700-odd rural
households relocated to the Hongge Migrant Area.
</P>
<P>
Fan told journalists from major Beijing press units that "her
new home cost more than 60,000 yuan and was constructed with
government assistance of 40,000 yuan."
</P>
<P>
An official with the Panzhihua Migrant Management Office said
that large groups of people are leaving the area surrounding the
new power station area.
</P>
<P>
The central government approved the establishment of Panzhihua
City in the early 1960s. The lightly populated young city, with a
history of 30-odd years, will grow by 32,000 people being
relocated from the site of the Ertan Power Station.
</P>
<P>
The Yanbian County seat and 15 local towns and townships will
also be inundated. Local officials note that construction of the
station will affect 1,567 hectares of arable land, 1,600 hectares
of forests and 1.4 million sq m of housing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
