<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Technical Associations Help Chinese Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A few apple growers in
Kuiwen Village in central China's Henan province set up their own
apple research association in the early 1990s and now get 65
percent of their income from apples.
</P>
<P>
The association invited experts to give lectures, sent farmers
to training courses, and held night classes, helping its members
learn about growing apples. Now, the village has 100 ha of apple
trees.
</P>
<P>
There are at least 10,000 technical associations in the
province with some 700,000 members. Chinese farmers first began to
form these associations in the early 1980s to get their
small-scale cottage industries to grow.
</P>
<P>
The associations provide a link between research institutes,
colleges, and farmers in the field of agronomy.
</P>
<P>
The provincial Association for Science and Technology
encourages farmers to set up company-household associations, and
supervises pilot projects of 300 associations. As a result, more
than 900 associations have grown into economic entities, bringing
the market closer to farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
