<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Senate Suggests Big Drop in Tax Collection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Senate today
projected a reduction of eight billion pesos (250 million U.S.
dollars) in the government's tax collections, due to the revision
downward of the gross national product (GNP) growth rate target.
</P>
<P>
Ernesto Herrera, chairman of the Finance Committee, said before
the Senate that the substantial reduction in tax collection is the
result of the move by the National Economic and Development
Authority to revise downward the GNP growth target from seven
percent to only 5-5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The authority revised its GNP growth target following a
slowdown in economic activity caused by rises in interest rates, a
20 percent plunge in the value of the Philippine peso and the
recent oil price increases.
</P>
<P>
The reduction in the GNP growth rate target could adversely
affect the government's financial standing, Herrera said, because
"tax collections already fell 22.2 billion pesos (693.8 million
dollars) short in the first seven months."
</P>
<P>
From January to July, the Bureau of Internal Revenue collected
183.5 billion pesos (5.7 billion dollars), which is 9.5 billion
(296.9 million dollars) short of its target.
</P>
<P>
The Bureau of Customs also fell 12.6 billion pesos (393.8
million dollars) short of its 49.4 billion pesos (1.5 billion
dollars) target.
</P>
<P>
Herrera also said a drop in the volume of the country's imports
as a result of the depreciation of the peso could worsen the
government's fiscal position.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Service Industry Booming in Czech Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, September 8 (Xinhua) -- After six years of rapid
growth, service industry is becoming the major part of Czech
Republic's economy.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of the service industry in the country's gross
domestic product (GDP), soared 46 percent from 37.5 in 1990 to
53.9 last year, said a spokesman from the National Statistics
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The service industry is also the leader in employment. At
present, 2.3 million people, or 63.8 percent of the total
employment population, are working in the sector.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, values generated by industry and
agriculture in the GDP, which were 53.9 and 8.6 percent in 1990,
went down to 41.2 and 4.9 percent respectively last year.
</P>
<P>
The population employed in industry and agriculture kept on
dwindling in the past six years, with industrial workers
decreasing from 2.03 million to 1.62 million.
</P>
<P>
Various types of new service business are mushrooming in the
capital Prague and other areas. Many daily problems in life that
puzzled people in the past are now readily solved.
</P>
<P>
The booming is attributed to the government's efforts to
readjust the industrial structure in recent years. After 1990, the
government has introduced a series of investment and tax revenue
policies to support the development of the service industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Company Accused of Scandal to Present Objections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The chief magistrate's court
in Nairobi has allowed five suspects in the Goldenberg scandal
case to present their objections before September 11, the "Daily
Nation" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Chief Magistrate Uniter Kidullah was quoted as saying that she
would hear submissions from the five suspects from September 17.
</P>
<P>
The five suspects are businessman Kamlesh Pattni, former
Treasury Permanent Secretary Wilfred Koinanage, former Deputy
Governor of the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) Eliphaz Riungu,
former CBK Chief Dealer Michael Wanjihia Onsmus and the
Pattni-owned Goldenberg International Ltd..
</P>
<P>
They were jointly charged in a 93-count indictment with
stealing 5.8 billion Kenyan Shillings (about 94 million U.S.
Dollars) belonging to the Kenyan government in a gold and diamond
export scandal.
</P>
<P>
The five suspects were released on bond in July following a
High Court ruling that 93 criminal charges against the five were
terminated.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government ordered that the suspects be charged
afresh and a 15-count indictment was presented in a Nairobi court
by Director of Public Prosecutions Bernard Chunga following the
withdrawal of previous charges.
</P>
<P>
The suspects represented by their lawers have denied all the
15 counts, saying the fresh indictment contained the same facts
and material that were successfully objected to.
</P>
<P>
The Goldenberg scandal case was reportedly cited as one of the
reasons why the International Monetary Fund (IMF) decided to
suspend a loan package to Kenya earlier this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
