<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CP Group Chairman Confident of Thai Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Dhanin Chearavanont, chairman
and chief executive officer of the Charoen Pokphand Group, said
Thailand's economic problems are not difficult to tackle.
</P>
<P>
Dhanin said the current crisis is not the worst Thailand has
ever experienced and that the country's fundamentals remain
healthy.
</P>
<P>
Besides, there are still a host of economic areas ripe for
development, the Bangkok Post today quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said if people do not lose confidence, the situation will
have returned to normal. A crisis of confidence is behind the
country's spiralling economic woes, he added.
</P>
<P>
Conceding that restoring public confidence is easier said than
done, he said that in the short term, the best thing politicians
can do to restore confidence is to stop quarrelling and work
together toward a common goal.
</P>
<P>
He said it was more difficult for a government to tackle
problems efficiently than a business because it was bound by a
bureaucratic system and sometimes unwieldy laws.
</P>
<P>
He said although the country's crisis is serious, it has not
affected the country's agricultural sector, which accounts for
about 60 percent of Thailand's gross product.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the weakening of the baht should soon lead to
stronger exports of agricultural products both in terms of value
and volume.
</P>
<P>
A weak baht should also effectively reduce imports,
particularly of luxury goods.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that Thailand move to open its skies to boost
tourism and bring in much-needed foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
He said Thailand could also offer more incentives to foreign
investors, such as permitting them to own land and giving them
more privileges in the country.
</P>
<P>
The CP Group has been built in only 40 years from a small firm
selling animal feed and pesticide to one of the largest business
conglomerates in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Under the CP Group umbrella there are over 400 companies at
home and aboard, covering nine main sectors, such as
agro-business, animal feed, real estate, foreign trade, vehicles,
telecommunications and electronics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
