<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Business Blasts GSP Cancellation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh Garment
Manufacturers and Exporters Association has strongly protested the
government decision to cancel 6,910 allegedly irregular GSP
certificates and termed it as a wrong step, the local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
"We deplore the government action," the association's
president, Mostafa Golam Quddus, said Monday after holding an
emergency meeting of the association's executive committee.
</P>
<P>
Following pressure from the European Commission (EC), the
government on Sunday canceled the certificates issued to 86
factories earlier for using the facility of the General System of
Preference (GSP) in exporting garments to the European market.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's garment industry, the biggest foreign-exchange
earner in this underdeveloped country, has been enjoying duty-free
or low-duty treatment under the GSP facility in the European
market.
</P>
<P>
Quddus said the government took a wrong decision on the GSP
unilaterally without consulting the trade bodies of the garment
sector and this would cause colossal losses to the country's
export earnings.
</P>
<P>
"It's now the responsibility of the government to bear all the
consequences of this action," he said, adding that the country
would suffer a serious image crisis in the international market.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, European importers of Bangladesh garments have
formed an association and is planning to claim about 100 million
dollars compensation from Dhaka after the cancellation of GSP
certificates.
</P>
<P>
Before canceling the certificates, the government should have
struck a deal with the EC so that such pressure does not come from
them in future, Quddus suggested.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government has already canceled 386 GSP
certificates and is still under pressure to take action against
8,568 others.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Stamp Auction Creates Record Selling Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A large stamp auction held in
Shanghai last Sunday featured more than 1,000 stamps issued during
the Qing Dynasty, the Kuomintang ruling period and after the
founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
A "blue army postage stamp" sold for 385,000 yuan (46,000 US
dollars), the highest auction price on record.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the aforementioned rare stamp was one of three army
postage stamps issued by the Ministry of Posts and
Telecommunications in 1953.
</P>
<P>
The auction, held by the Shanghai International Commodities
Auction Corp. Ltd., attracted more than 1,000 stamp collectors
from both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 percent of stamps on offer were sold for over 5.26
million yuan (about 640,000 U.S. dollars) during the 10-hour auction.
</P>
<P>
Experts note that stamps without floor prices proved to be the
best-selling items and accounted for some 12 percent of total
sales.  
</P>
</TEXT>
