<HEADLINE> Chinese Journalists Join Anti-Poverty Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Lu Deming, a journalist from
the provincial television broadcasting station in Yunnan, a
backward area populated by ethnic minorities in the southwestern
part of China, often visits poor villages to report about
conditions there.
</P>
<P>
And villagers welcome him. In the words of one farmer: "Your
visit has brought us care from the government and the Party."
</P>
<P>
Lu believes that, as a journalist, he should do something
more. There are journalists like him who have found a new way to
help poverty-stricken people and who are participating in
poverty-eradication efforts by writing stories that describe the
reality of life in poor areas to make people on the outside more
aware.
</P>
<P>
This year, more than 100 correspondents from various news media
in Yunnan have been sent to poor villages, where they have filed
more than 1,000 stories. Early this year, the China Journalists
Association called for media to join the anti-poverty campaign.
</P>
<P>
Local journalists have been once criticized by some people for
their coverage of richer areas and the lack of reports on poorer
places. So, recently, Chinese papers have provided special columns
on the poverty-elimination campaign. The response across the
country has been good, and readers and members of audiences have
written to newspapers and radio and TV stations expressing their
concern.
</P>
<P>
A provincial government official in charge of Yunnan's news
media told Xinhua that the media really can have an effect. Yunnan
TV recently had a charity program that got 2.9 million yuan in
donations from industry and media. The money will be used to build
primary schools for the Hope Project, a nationwide program to help
children from poor families. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
