<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Workshop on Climate Held in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A five-day regional forum on a
consolidated climate forecast for the coming rainy season opened
Monday in Kadoma, central Zimbabwe, against the background of El
Nino which is building up in the pacific ocean, reported the
Zimbabwe News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The forum which brought together more than 50 scientists,
researchers and meteorologists from the southern African region
aims to provide guidance in social-economic decision making and
management activities to governments in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Southern African Development Community (SADC) countries
represented at the forum will design a criteria to promote high
standards in the development of forecast methodologies and the
evolution of new techniques and approaches.
</P>
<P>
Marufu Zinyowera, Director of the Department of Meteorological
Services in Zimbabwe said at the opening ceremony that the forum
is designed to "further strengthen the regional capacity to
produce, distribute and utilize climate forecast information in
climate-sensitive sectors for the social and economic benefit of
the region."
</P>
<P>
"The forum will also resolve gaps in training and technical
capacity, facilitate research cooperation and data exchange and
promote on-going dialogue between forecast users and producers,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the director noted, El Nino was expected to cause
only five percent of the drought in southern Africa, while in
Zimbabwe the phenomemon was said to be responsible for 32 percent
of the droughts.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's Transport and Energy Deputy Minister Zenso Nsimbi
urged researchers and meteorologists in the region to come up
with concrete actions designed to improve the capabilities and
provide credible seasonal forecasts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
