<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Astronomers Find Way To Predict Earthquakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese astronomers are using
their instruments to predict earthquakes in a network from Beijing
to Yunnan province in the southwest.
</P>
<P>
Beijing, capital of the nation, needs to be protected from
earthquake damage and Yunnan is one of the most frequently hit
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The instruments are used to measure changes in the earth's
rotation, which Chinese astronomers connected to earthquakes by
studying one that hit Tangshan, a middle-sized city about 200 km
from Beijing, 20 years ago, killing hundreds of thousands of
people.
</P>
<P>
Scientists found that when a strong earthquake was going to
hit, the earth's rotational data is different from that in other
parts of the world. This difference can occur several weeks or
months before the earthquake hits, and it returns to normal not
long after the earthquake hits.
</P>
<P>
The difference is the result of the distance of the instrument
from the epicenter and is related to the magnitude of the
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
The instrument uses a plumb line and changes in its angle are
used for the results. Scientists found that unusual changes in the
plumb line before an earthquake hit an area.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary work came from a research project of the
Beijing, Yunnan, Shanghai observatories and the Yunnan Seismology
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The Yunnan Observatory has provided the local government with
accurate earthquake information six times in recent years. The
Beijing and Shaanxi observatories have been doing the research
work in cooperation with the United States and Russia
respectively, and an effort is being made to set up networks in
areas frequently hit by earthquakes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
