<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea to Narrow Trade Gap With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Seoul's widening trade gap with Washington, if left uncurbed,
would seriously threaten the nation's current account balance this
year, said officials of the Ministry of Economy and Finance.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry, South Korea's exports to the
U.S. in the first seven months of this year declined 6.6 percent
to 12.1 billion from a year earlier, while imports fell only 2.6
percent to 18.7 billion, causing the trade gap to widen to 6.6
billion.
</P>
<P>
The deficit in two-way trade with Washington accounted for 67
percent of the country's total trade shortfall of 9.86 billion
U.S. dollars during the cited period.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the widening trade deficit to South
Korea's weak competitiveness of export goods against that of their
Japanese counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, South Korean export interest in the U.S. market have
noticeably cooled off in recent years because of the dwindling
numbers of U.S. branches and their staff members dispatched by
South Korean trading companies, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has asked the trading representatives to redouble
U.S. marketing efforts and to develop new export markets of
government procurement and electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
So, the ministry plans to collect information on U.S.
administration's purchasing plans and their buying agencies on
behalf of local exporters.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean trade officials will also call on their U.S.
counterparts to ensure greater accesses to the U.S. procurement
market for South Korean companies in view of rectifying the heavy
trade imbalance in favor of Washington, when they meet in an
inaugural meeting of South Korea-U.S. business cooperation
committee next month, according to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's exports to the U.S. had risen by 10 percent
annually until mid-1980s, thanks to such favorable environmental
factors as low interest rates, weakening dollar against the yen
and low oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The export gains rate slowed to 4.5 percent on the annual
average between 1990 and 1995 before marking a yearly drop of 10.2
percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, imports from the U.S. has shown annual
increase of over 10 percent since the 1990s, widening the trade
deficit from 1 billion dollars in 1994 to 6.3 billion dollars in
1995 and to 11.6 billion dollars last year, which represented 56
percent of its total trade gap, the ministry figures indicated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
