<HEADLINE> Industry Shows Uptrend Signs in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- India's industry is showing
signs of an upward trend in 1997-98 fiscal year(April 1,
1997-March 31,1998).
</P>
<P>
"It emerges from the study that the cyclical components of
certain leading indicators of industrial activities like non-food
bank credit, all-India financial institutions' approvals, primary
capital market activity and non-oil imports (in terms of U.S.
dollars) are showing a gradual upward movement on a month-to-month
basis," said the latest study released by Industrial Credit and
Investment Corporation of India (ICICI).
</P>
<P>
This coupled with a low level of interest rates signal a future
uptrend in industrial activities. A steeper growth is forecast in
total deposits and money supply in the coming months and it also
suggests that there will not be any constraints on the supply of
loanable funds to the industry. This would help revive industrial
performance. The study said that the industrial output would show
an uptrend from June, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Other factors which underpin the potential for improved
industrial performance during 1997-98 are a good agricultural crop
in 1996-97 and the prospects for another favorable one in 1997-98
providing stimulus to rural demand, corporate and intermediate
goods production during April-may this year, the study further
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
