<HEADLINE> More Gongolese (K) Refugees Go Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Another batch of
refugees, numbering 551, from the Democratic Republic of Congo
have left Tanzania's port of Kigoma for Congo's Uvira port on
Lake Tanganyika.
</P>
<P>
The refugees who had been lived in Lugufu and Nyarugushu camps
in Kigoma Region went home on Monday on a voluntary repatriation
operantion, according to a news dispatch from Kigoma.
</P>
<P>
About 12,000 Congolese refugees have already been registered
for voluntary repatriation and about 5,000 others are being
registered for the same purpose, said Osmand douglas, the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) Logistic Officer
in Kigoma sub-office, after the refugees left Kigoma.
</P>
<P>
Last Monday, about 600 Congolese refugees returned home from
Tanzania. Upon their arrival, Uvira district Commissioner Bashire
Kusebana told them to forget their refugee category and recognize
themselves as pure Congolese.
</P>
<P>
Congo (K) has called on its refugees hosted in Tanzania to
return home and join fellow citizens in re-building the nation.
</P>
<P>
Congolese Foreign Minister Bizima Karaha said in Dar es Salaam
on September 5, "We have made arrangements between the government
of Congo, Tanzania and the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) for the refugees to be repatriated home on
voluntary basis."
</P>
<P>
He said, "We do not want antagonism. The country can only be
run by congolese and not anybody elso. So for those who fear that
the government will take them to task after returning home should
be rest assured that they will be safe."  
</P>
</TEXT>
