<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing Witnesses Less Acid Rain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing, an industrial
city in southwest China, has witnessed significant declines in
acid rain due to lower levels of sulfur dioxide in the air.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the Chongqing Environmental Protection
Bureau show that levels of acid rain have dropped from 90 percent
to 60 percent of total rainfall, with the sulfur dioxide content
in the air falling to 0.28 milligrams per cubic meter, a drop of
30 percent as compared with that five years ago.
</P>
<P>
Experts attribute the phenomenon to the strict control of waste
gases discharged from factories, the use of clean fuel such as
coal gas, natural gas, and more rainfall during spring season.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing, a city known for its heavy fog, is often enveloped
in a dense "atmosphere cover."
</P>
<P>
Dust control projects were launched in densely populated areas
and other downtown district and the local government banned the
use of coal in the city's 4,000 restaurants.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing has also installed additional sulfur removal
facilities in factories using coal and oil. Technical upgrades of
boilers in a number of factories have also reduced levels of
polluting gases
</P>
<P>
The city, one of China's four municipalities directly under the
Central Government, has been also amongst China's first group of 13
major cities reporting air quality levels.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
