<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Period Shortened for Thai Exporters to Hold Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Thai exporters have been
requested to shorten the period during which they can hold their
foreign exchange income from 180 days to 120 days.
</P>
<P>
Within 15 days, exporters must sell U.S. dollars to banks or
change the money and deposit it in non-resident baht accounts,
according to an announcement of the central bank of Thailand on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The steps are aimed at improving dollar supply, curbing
speculation on the foreign exchange market and easing the cash
shortage affecting some banks and finance companies, said Bank of
Thailand Governor Chayawat Wibulswasdi.
</P>
<P>
He said the measures would improve the demand and supply
balance in the market for dollars, adding that the 120-day limit
is appropriate for exporters as 70 percent of them are paid within
three weeks of shipment.
</P>
<P>
Depositors must show that they have obligations to meet within
90 days in order to deposit dollar income in non-resident
foreign-currency accounts.
</P>
<P>
Thai people who want to buy dollars for their overseas trips
will now be required to show their passports and travel tickets.
</P>
<P>
Chayawat said that since the baht's floatation on July 2, the
number of non-resident baht accounts has increased from 2,600 to
3,600, mostly for speculation on the strengthening dollar.
</P>
<P>
The baht recovered to about 36 against the U.S. dollar late
Monday, as compared with a record low of 38.4 last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The local currency has depreciated more than 40 percent since
its floatation on July 2.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates on the central bank's bond repurchase market
remained high at 24 percent on Monday as the central bank tried to
curb speculation on the strengthening dollar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
