<HEADLINE> Dhaka Provides Loan for Crisis-Ridden Food Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh Bank, the central
bank, has decided to extend credit support to salvage the
country's crisis-ridden frozen food sector following the European
Union's ban on seafood from Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources said the bank is to provide 4 million taka
(about 90,000 U.S. dollars) to each of the entrepreneurs to
upgrade their processing units in keeping with EU standard
regulations.
</P>
<P>
The EU imposed the ban on import of frozen foods from
Bangladesh on July 30 this year, alleging that they do not comply
with EU rules and regulations concerning quality control.
</P>
<P>
However, Bangladesh was given until the coming November to
improve its product quality.
</P>
<P>
Under the fresh loan program, some 160 million taka (about 3.6
million dollars) will be disbursed among 40 entrepreneurs to
renovate their units to meet the EU Hazard Analysis Critical
Central Point (HACCP) requirements.
</P>
<P>
Although loans amounting to 5.33 billion taka (about 121
million dollars) remain outstanding with various financial
institutions by the sector, the central bank decided to extend the
credit in view of the sector's contribution to the country's total
export performance.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh exported frozen foods worth 320.73 million dollars
in the 1996-97 fiscal year, accounting for 7 percent of the
country's total export earnings.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
