<HEADLINE> Early Retirement Plan for Thai Civil Servants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Civil Service
Commission (CSC) has given the green light to an early retirement
program as part of efforts to promote the efficiency of government
organs.
</P>
<P>
The program, which is aimed at reducing the number of civil
servants by 38,000 in the country by 2000, was passed at a meeting
of the commission chaired by Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The program will be carried out strictly on a voluntary basis
with those choosing to go being paid with special benefits, said
Adul Boonprakorb, secretary-general of the CSC.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has two million civil servants working at various
government bodies nationwide, accounting for about six percent of
the country's labor force.
</P>
<P>
However, local newspapers said that only about 300,000 of these
civil servants are under the CSC. Teachers, police and military
personnel, and judicial officials are not under the administration
of the CSC.  
</P>
