<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors Confident in Sri Lanka's Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A strong surge of foreign
investment in Sri Lanka in 1996 shows investors are confident in
the nation's economic environment, the latest statistics from the
Board of Investment (BOI) revealed.
</P>
<P>
The BOI has approved 345 projects valued at 457 billion rupees
(about 7.75 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment components of these projects stood at 432
billion rupees (7.33 billion U.S. dollars), accounting for 95
percent of the total investment value, compared with local
investment of 25 billion rupees (425 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The massive rise in the value of total estimated investment
from 35 billion rupees (598 million dollars) in 1995 is attributed
to the sizable investment of three petroleum processing plants
approved last year.
</P>
<P>
The foreign investment components of these projects represented
a 238 percent rise over the previous year of 1995.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the BOI said investors who have established
manufacturing bases in Sri Lanka have demonstrated their
confidence in the country's economic environment by both expanding
and diversifying their operations.
</P>
<P>
He added that the overall performance of BOI enterprises in the
spheres of investment, export earnings and job creation underline
their contribution to the country's export-oriented industrial
strategy.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996 there were a total of 11,130 BOI approved
enterprises in commercial operation.
</P>
<P>
The value of annual export earnings grew from 6.4 billion
rupees (108 million dollars) in 1986 to 133 billion rupees (2.26
billion dollars) in 1996, accounting for 58 percent of Sri Lanka's
total export earnings for that year.
</P>
<P>
The number of workers employed in these projects has also risen
from 123,359 in 1990 to 271,179 in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
