<HEADLINE> Nepal to Curb Expenses in Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 9 (Xinhua) -- An all-party committee has
been formed to curb the lavish expenses within the Parliament,
Nepali Lower House Speaker Ram Chandra Poudel said.
</P>
<P>
In response to growing concerns over irregularities in the
Parliament, Poudel announced Monday in the Lower House that
meeting between party representatives are continuing to find out
ways and means to bring the expenses to a minimum, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Former finance minister Ram Sharan Mahat claimed that the food
and beverage bills for the Prime Minister's Office within the
parliament premises reached 53,000 rupees (about 930 U.S.
dollars), while the Parliament has paid 5.8 million rupees (about
101,700 dollars) to its cafeteria for supplying products for
lawmakers attending various parliamentary meetings.
</P>
<P>
Mahat, a MP from the main opposition the Nepali Congress,
further alleged that 22 cabinet members of the present government
are taking dual benefits and salaries as ministers and MPs.
</P>
<P>
Besides, bottled drinking water is excessively used in the
Parliament, local press reports claimed.
</P>
<P>
Last month, some MPs were alleged of presenting false medical
and expense bills and extracting large sums from the Parliament
Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the Lower House Finance Committee had
directed the Parliament cafeteria to stop supplying bottled water
for the lawmakers to curb costs charged to the Parliament
Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of heavy public criticism about what is widely
called as "pajero culture," the Communist Party of Nepal (United
Marxist-Leninist, CPN-UML) has decided to instruct its MPs not to
import any new vehicles under the privilege that exempts the
import duties, and return such vehicles to the government.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 percent MPs have imported expensive vehicles
duty-free, press reports said.
</P>
<P>
The former government led by Sher Bahadur Deuba gave such a
privilege to the MPs, which has come under heavy criticism from
the public.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
