<HEADLINE> Big Companies in Race for Order From Indian Airlines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Several big global companies
such as Allied Signal, Rockwell Collions and Airbus are in a race
in a stiff competition to bag the huge order of airborne collision
avoidance system (ACAS) from the Indian Airlines, highly placed
sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Airlines has over 50 aircraft and it's ACAS order
would be the biggest in the country. According to rough estimates,
it has to spend over 350 million rupees (9.86 million U.S.
dollars) for fitting it's entire fleet with ACAS equipment. For
installing both mode 's' transponder and ACAS, Indian Airlines
might have to spend 117.5 million rupees (3.31 million dollars)
per aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The France-based aircraft manufacturer Airbus Industrie has
also shown interest in the deal. This is in view of the fact that
40 aircraft in the Indian Airlines fleet are the products of the
Airbus Industrie. Airbus is reportedly felt to be in a better
position to do the necessary retrofitting since it knows the
a300/a320 design better than others.
</P>
<P>
It is known in many parts of the world that the Indian Airlines
Board has directed the company to go in for speedy installation of
ACAS or traffic alert and collision avoidance system (TCAS).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
