<HEADLINE> President Ramos, Cardinal to Meet on Charter Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos and the influential Manila Archbishop Jaime Cardinal Sin
will meet again tonight at dinner on the burning issue of
constitutional change, the local press reported.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is a fresh effort to repair relations between the
president and the archbishop and thwart a September 21 protest
rally against charter change to be organized by the Roman Catholic
Church, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Tonight's dinner at the archbishop's residence will mark the
third meeting in the past few days between the president and
Cardinal Sin, since they exchanged potshots over the charter
change issue.
</P>
<P>
Also attending the meeting will be former President Corazon
Aquino, a strong opponent of the charter change, and several
cabinet members who are known charter change advocates.
</P>
<P>
Sin was quoted as saying the dinner meeting will be held behind
closed doors, with the high-profile "visitors" expected to have a
lively exchange of views.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear what items will be on the agenda of today's
dinner but Sin hinted that it will center on the issue of charter
change.
</P>
<P>
The meeting comes after priests and other charter change
critics mounted the first day of their protracted protest noise
barrage last night.
</P>
<P>
Motorists and residents in parts of Manila honked their horns
and banged pots and pans while church bells were rung across the
capital city, as part of the run-up activities to the September
rally.
</P>
<P>
During their last two encounters early this month, Ramos
appealed to Sin to call off the planned protest rally but he was
rebuffed by the prelate.
</P>
<P>
With accusations and speculations mounting that Ramos kept his
options open for a second term, the president Monday assured the
nation in a broadcast statement yesterday that he will not seek to
scrap the 1998 polls and impose martial law.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, who must step down in June 1998 as provided for by the
constitution when his one single six-year term expires, also made
it clear that he is "against term extension."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
