<HEADLINE> Southern Peru on Health Alert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A health alert was declared today
in the city of Tacna, south of Peru, after a mortal virus named
Hanta killed a young man in the neighboring Chilean city of Arica.
</P>
<P>
Nineteen cases of the disease have been reported in the past
few days in Chilean cities of Punta Arenas, Santiago, Iquique and
Arica. The virus has an incubation period of seven to 16 days,
said health officials.
</P>
<P>
Health institutions in Tacna said they have demanded 17 sectors
in the city implement rodent controls. Hanta virus is found in
their urine and excrement. The human being will get infected when
their food is contaminated by the virus.
</P>
<P>
As part of the health alert, all cargo ships entering Tacna and
the train station in the city will be fumigated, they said.
</P>
<P>
Health authorities said Tacna`s wholesales fish market, a
high-risk site, will be closed for three days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
