<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vicunas on Verge of Extinction in South Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Vicunas are on the verge of
extinction due to uncontrolled illegal hunting in the southern
Andes zone of Peru.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Department of Arequipa said that in southern
Peru, local farmers have been asked to kill vicunas by furtive
hunters working for organized traders who traffick vicuna wool in
the black market.
</P>
<P>
President of the Nature Protection Organization, Mauricio de
Romana, said the situation had caused a 20 percent reduction of
vicunas in the zone.
</P>
<P>
A vicuna count carried out in 1994 by the Ministry of
Agriculture showed there were 2,079 vicunas in Arequipa, but now
about 400 have been killed to misuse their wool and skin.
</P>
<P>
Romana said the need to implement strict surveillance in the
areas to protect the animal was urgent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
