<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (Part I) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
news briefs from Latin American countries in the past few days:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The Argentine government's financial deficit
shrank sharply from 302 million U.S. dollars in August 1996 to 7
million dollars in August 1997, the Economic Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The 284 million dollar income from the privatization of the
Mortgage Bank balanced the treasury, added the ministry.
</P>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA -- Fuel Consumption in Colombia during the
first seven months rose 5.43 percent compared to the same period
last year, reported the state-owned oil company Ecopetrol.
</P>
<P>
The daily volume of fuel burned during the period was 246,177
barrels.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazilian pork exports in January-July climbed 28
percent in volume and 45 percent in value compared with the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Brazil exported 33,600 tons of pork, which was worth 78 million
U.S. dollars during the period.
</P>
<P>
The main buyers for Brazilian pork are Argentina and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- A total of 405,000 tourists visited Costa Rica from
January to July, the Institute of Tourism (ICT) said.
</P>
<P>
The ICT estimated about 820,000 foreign visitors may come to
the country by the year's end, a 5 percent increase over
1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American News Briefs (Part II) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- The Brazilan government plans to designate 20
million added hectares in Amazonia for the production of grains,
Alberto Duque Portugal, the president of the Agriculture Company
of Brazil, said.
</P>
<P>
The first stage will be implemented in nine Amazonian
districts, with an investment of 560,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Cement demand in Mexico will rise in 1997-1998,
because of the ongoing economic recovery, the financial group
Banamex-Accival (Banacci) said in a study report.
</P>
<P>
The report predicted the demand for cement will reach 24.4
million tons in 1997 and 26.5 million tons in 1998.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- A total of 124,000 new jobs were created in several
economic sectors in Chile from May 1996 to July 1997, up 2.4
percent from the same period last year, the Labor and Social
Security Ministry reported.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the increasing job opportunities to
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Nicaragua's Central American Credit Bank (Bancentro)
will issue "Agriculture and Livestock Investment Certificates"
(Centiagros) bonds, worth 10 million U.S. dollars, to help loan
farmers and manufacturers of agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
According to an accord signed over the weekend, the
Inter-American Corporation of Investment and Bancentro itself will
be responsible for the bond sales.
</P>
<P>
Most of the bonds will be sold to foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Automobile sales in Uruguay reached 20,161
vehicles in the first eight months, an increase of 22.3 percent,
over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The brands Fiat, Chevrolet and Volkswagen had a 40.6 percent
share of the Uruguayan automobile market from January to August.
</P>
</TEXT>
