<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baby Found with Translocated Internal Organs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Doctors at a military hospital
here have reported the case of a newborn girl whose internal
organs are on the reverse sides of her body cavity.
</P>
<P>
On September 2, doctors at the hospital in this capital of East
China's Shandong province examined a baby girl using color Doppler
ultrasonic equipment, and discovered that the baby's heart and
spleen were on the right side of her chest, and her liver,
gallbladder and pancreas were on the left.
</P>
<P>
Doctors say translocated internal organs are rare, and to have
all five main internal organs displaced is even more so.
</P>
<P>
They explain that the malformation occurs during the period in
which a fertilized egg is developing into an embryo, and the
baby's organs are undergoing a complicated rotation process to
reach their normal locations.
</P>
<P>
If the rotation is stopped for any reason, the displacement of
the developed organs occurs.
</P>
<P>
The military hospital has sent the girl to the local social
welfare house and decided to provide her with long-term health
care.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Rupiah Strengthens as Stock Prices Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's currency, the
rupiah, strengthened against the U.S. dollar Monday and stock
prices increased 1 percent following broad recovery in the region,
dealers and brokers here said today.
</P>
<P>
They said confidence had gradually returned to currency and
stock markets after a new reform package was announced last week.
</P>
<P>
Spot rupiah, which opened at 2,920/2,930 against the U.S.
dollar, weakened to the 2,960 level in morning trading but then
strengthened in the afternoon to close at 2,905/2,915.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta Stock Exchange Composite Index, the main share
price gauge on the exchange, crossed the 600-point level to close
at 600.311 points, up 6.199 points from last Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
Stockbrokers said the rise in share prices over the past few
days was boosted by the government's reform package, especially
the interest rate cut and scrapping of the limit of 49 percent to
foreign portfolio ownership.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government on September 3 revealed a 10-point
plan that covered imports and exports, banking and capital
markets, taxes and budget spending cuts.
</P>
<P>
As a follow-up step, the central bank on September 4 cut its
benchmark Bank Indonesia Certificate (SBI) interest rates by 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
Since then, share prices on the stock exchange have risen more
than 20 percent and the rupiah remained stable.
</P>
<P>
Analysts held that the government should further decrease
interest rates and ease the tight monetary policy to push the
recovery of the capital market.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the currency crisis in Southeast Asian
countries, the rupiah has fallen nearly 23 percent since January
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
