<HEADLINE> Science in China's Economic Development (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Agronomy has contributed
greatly to increased crop yields in China, an example of the
impact of scientific developments, according to the State Science
and Technology Commission.
</P>
<P>
Mianyang City in southwest China's Sichuan Province has become
the country's second largest electronics center after seven years
of work. Industrial output in the city increased 35 percent
annually, more than the average of relatively developed eastern
parts of China.
</P>
<P>
This is attributed to the use of science in economic
development, contributing about 45 percent of the city's economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, China's leading industrial city, new materials,
optical fiber, micro-electronic products, and computer science
have attracted more than 50,000 scientists to the hi-tech
development field.
</P>
<P>
Scientists are also involved in communications, iron and steel
and automobiles. In the first six months of this year, the output
value of the six pillar industries accounted for over 50 percent
of the city's total industrial output.
</P>
<P>
The central government's policy is one of seeking sustainable
social and economic development by relying on science and
education, and of 30,000 science developments during the Eighth
Five-Year Plan period (1991-1995), 25,000 have been used in
industrial production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
