<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Science in China's Economic Development (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The country's technology transfer contracts were worth 30
billion yuan (3.65 billion US dollars) in the past few years. And
although the market economy has solved quite a number problems,
key science discoveries in agriculture, energy, communications,
space, and other hi-tech fields are important to the government.
</P>
<P>
China has a nine-year compulsory education program that cost
over 10 billion yuan in government funds. It is in place in half
of China, and from 1990 to 1996, about four million people learned
to read and write each year, and 440 million adults received
further training.
</P>
<P>
To rejuvenate the country with science and technology,
personnel and investment are the two most important things. So, to
attract Chinese experts and scholars from abroad, a number of
hi-tech ventures like the Founders' Group and Legend have
established research centers abroad and some preferential
conditions have been developed.
</P>
<P>
In June of this year, the Qinghua Higher Research Center was
established by dozens of well known overseas Chinese scientists,
and at China's Academy of Sciences, the top research body, more
than half the researchers are below the age of 45.  
</P>
</TEXT>
