<HEADLINE> Myanmar Strives to Wipe Out Illiteracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is making efforts to
provide all children with primary education by the year 2000 and
reduce the adult illiteracy rate to 11 percent from the present 22
percent, a senior Myanmar education official said.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Education U Pan Aung told a meeting on literacy
Monday that generating higher income and ensuring better life for
the people, coupled with a literacy drive, will be carried out
phase by phase in more than 300 townships over three years
beginning this year, the official paper The New Light of Myanmar
reported today.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized efforts to include all ethnic groups, including
those in the border areas, in the project, to enable them to learn
the Myanmar language.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's adult illiteracy rate has been gradually brought down
to 29 percent in 1973 and further to the present 22 percent thanks
to a literacy drive launched in the country in 1964.  
</P>
</TEXT>
