<HEADLINE> Russian, French Foreign Ministers Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov met today with his French counterpart, Hubert
Vedrine, and the two discussed bilateral relations, Bosnia and the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said there are no major differences between the two
countries affecting their ties as they share the same views on
many international issues.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine arrived here Sunday for a two-day working visit.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the Bosnian situation, the Russian foreign minister
said Moscow does not agree with carrying out the Dayton peace
accord by eliminating or splitting the Bosnian Serb Republic.
</P>
<P>
Both sides expressed hope that all sides involved contribute to
the success of the coming local elections scheduled for this month
in the Serb Republic.
</P>
<P>
On Middle East, Primakov said his country will support any
position promoting the peace process put forward by any country.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said Russia is strongly against any form of terrorism,
but opposes the view that the peace process can only be started
when terrorism is rooted out.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said France hopes the United States, Germany, Russia,
the European Union and other countries will join in efforts for a
political resolution of the Middle East issue.
</P>
<P>
The two also exchanged views on preparations for French
President Jacques Chirac's visit to Russia at the end of the
month, and on the first session of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organisation-Russia Permanent Joint Council this autumn in New
York. 
</P>
