<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Models Staggering on Catwalk of Market Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Too many Ukrainian models vying
for limited catwalks have made themselves unbelievably cheap. A
beautiful girl rarely earns more than 150 U.S. dollars a month and
an average one often has to wait three to four months between jobs.
</P>
<P>
Many girls do not even get the chance to participate in mass
shows during their modeling careers, explains Halyna Logvinova,
manager of L-Models agency.
</P>
<P>
"People entering the profession here aren't doing it for money
but for popularity and image," he said.
</P>
<P>
By the beginning of this year, nearly 20 modeling agencies had
sprung up in the Ukrainian capital of Kiev, which is the national
hub of the popular industry, since the country gained independence
in 1991. An agency normally has a stable of 20-30 models, but
keeps another 80-200 young women on file.
</P>
<P>
Every agency has a school of its own. While more than 600 girls
graduate from these schools a year, only 20 fashion shows are held
annually in Kiev each requiring only 10 models.
</P>
<P>
The industry is suffering from over supply and inadequate
demand. The models who participated in the Lapidus collection show
earlier this year received only 10-20 hryvnas (5.5 to 11 dollars)
each.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's economic problems have a direct impact on the
modeling industry. Large western companies enter the Ukrainian
market with their own ready-made photos and videos. They seldom
require the services of local models.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian companies, on the other hand, either have no money
for advertising or are doing well in the shadow sector that
requires no advertising.
</P>
<P>
In order to survive, modeling agencies have expanded their
services. Models have to acquire general abilities, such as
working at exhibition booths, promoting merchandise at company
presentations and even dancing at nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
The best pay usually comes from working at trade shows and
exhibitions, where large numbers of girls are needed and clients
are not as demanding. The average rate for this type of work is
100 dollars for five days.
</P>
<P>
Currently, modeling agencies earn most of their profits from
running schools. Kiev schools charge 130 dollars on average for a
six-week modeling course. Groups of 15-20 girls are trained at a
time, though only about three of the hopefuls have any real chance
to get a job.
</P>
<P>
Professional models receive about five dollars an hour to teach
a variety of subjects such as photography, make-up, posture,
walking and etiquette.
</P>
<P>
Another source of income is exporting models for either
permanent or long-term assignments. Slavic fashion models are
becoming popular in the West, but this business often
backfires.
</P>
<P>
Once a girl gets a foothold in a host country, she often casts
the Ukrainian company behind her back.
</P>
<P>
"We seem to be a victim of the beauties who are working
abroad," complains Iryna Pavlova, director of the Dinamo Star
Agency. The agency regularly exports two girls to western
countries a year.
</P>
<P>
Pavlova predicts that the Ukrainian modeling industry will not
have a real chance to take off unless the country's overall
economic conditions improve. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Sees Rising Labor Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Thailand saw 10,881 labor
dispute cases during the first eight months of this year, a record
over the past 17 years, the Thai Central Labor Court said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the cases brought to the court were related to laid-off
workers' demand for compensation from their employers who closed
their businesses due to the economic slump, and suits by financial
institutions against their employees for granting excessive loans
to clients, the court said.
</P>
<P>
The cases brought to the court during the eight months involved
a total of 2.48 billion baht (about 70 million U.S. dollars),
according to the court.
</P>
<P>
The court also said it received 10,327 cases during the same
period of last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
