<HEADLINE> Crew to Restart Mir Computer After Repair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The crew of Russia's Mir space
station will try to restart the main computer on board today,
ground control said.
</P>
<P>
The computer failed Monday, hitting energy supplies aboard the
craft, but the crew fixed a faulty part in the computer, a
spokesman with Mission Control said.
</P>
<P>
They were likely to try to restart the computer after a radio
exchange with ground control at around 0500 GMT.
</P>
<P>
Mir collided with a cargo ship on June 25. Since then,
cosmonauts have had to handle one trouble after another on the
11-year-old station.
</P>
<P>
In July, one of the crew unplugged the main computer by
mistake, sending Mir spinning uncontrolled for about a day. In
August, a computer section crashed during a re-docking operation
with similar results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
