<HEADLINE> German Soccer Players Share Victory With Egyptian Orphans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Children at an Egyptian
orphanage had a special treat today when they caressed gifts and
shared laughter with teenage footballers from Germany.
</P>
<P>
In a move to bolster the flagging sportsmanship, the German
Under-17 national delegation took a day off to visit the SOS
Children's Village in Nasr City near Cairo.
</P>
<P>
An hour-and-half visit culminated in a lighthearted soccer
match in the village playground between the children and the
German players.
</P>
<P>
The children were overwhelmed with joy as the match resulted in
a shock 2-0 "victory" for the disadvantaged Egyptian children.
</P>
<P>
German coach Bernad Stober said that his boys would do better
against the real Egyptian team in their final group A match in
Cairo on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The German team, which has beaten Chile and Thailand in group
matches, has become the first of 16 teams to take a quarter-final
berth.
</P>
<P>
The Germans' visit followed a similar one by the Austrian
delegation to a SOS Children's Village near the Mediterranean port
of Alexandria last week.
</P>
<P>
Both visits were arranged within the framework of a project
called FIFA For SOS Children's Villages, by which the world soccer
ruling body and the football family give help to SOS villages in
128 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
The German players and officials clearly enjoyed the visit to
the village as much as the children, who sang and danced for the
visitors and showed them around two of the houses where they live
with their adopted families.
</P>
<P>
The young players gave the children German T-shirts and
pennants while FIFA Director of Communications, Keith Cooper,
distributed gifts including sports shoes, sportswear, footballs
and bags.
</P>
<P>
In its latest move to rekindle the declining spirit of
sportsmanship, FIFA has designated September 20-21 as the first
World Fair Play Days.
</P>
<P>
The second of the Fair Play Days will coincide with the final
match of the 7th FIFA Under-17 World Championship planned for
Egypt on September 4-21.
</P>
<P>
Cooper told Xinhua that FIFA's nearly 200 member associations
will stage a variety of activities to attract attention on fair
play during the two days of September, the busiest month for the
sport all over the world.
</P>
<P>
On September 21, "fair play team" from the Under-17 Worlds will
receive a 10,000-Swiss-Franc award and can donate it to Egypt's
SOS Children's Villages, FIFA-funded program established in
Austria 15 years ago, Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
Cooper criticized a rising tendency among professional players
to seek fame and fortune while neglecting moral integrity.
</P>
<P>
"Teams now prefer to win cups and medals and consider fair play
only secondary. It is more difficult to encourage media to
support the principle of fair play," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
