<HEADLINE> German Spikers Beat Russians in Group Preliminaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A timely yellow booking and
scores of solid blocking paid Germany fabulous dividend as it got
the better of Russia in a group preliminary match at the European
men's volleyball championship on Monday.
</P>
<P>
It took the Germans more than three hours to win a five-set
thriller from the Russians who created a major upset on Sunday by
blanking world league titlists Italy in the group A actions at
Bois-le-Duc.
</P>
<P>
With two sets in hand, the Germans seemed to become another
team by dropping the ensuing two sets.
</P>
<P>
With the Russians leading 10-6 in the tie-breaking fifth set,
the Germans finally found their form again and blocked the Russian
smashes only to turn the table around at last, winning their
third-round outing 15-9, 15-10, 6-15, 4-15, 16-14.
</P>
<P>
A yellow-card booking from the chair umpire awarded the Germans
a critical point after a 14-all tie with serving rights in hand
while a super one-man block returned the ball onto the right side
of the sideline at back court for the match winner.
</P>
<P>
The Russians also got a free point from a booking on the part
of the Germans earlier in the match.
</P>
<P>
In the day's other matches, Italy defeated Slovakia three sets
to one in group A while France blanked Bulgaria 3-0 and Ukraine
whitewashed Finland, both in group B at Eindhoven.
</P>
