<HEADLINE> Arizona's New Governor Sworn in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State Jane Dee
Hull has been sworn in as the new governor of Arizona of the
United States less than a week after former Governor Fife
Symington was convicted of seven federal fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Supreme Court Justice Sandra Day O'Connor was on hand to
administer the oath, The United Press International reported.
</P>
<P>
Hull was elected to the state House of Representatives in 1979
and became the first woman speaker of the House 10 years later.
</P>
<P>
Hull became governor after Symington's resignation took effect
last Friday following his conviction on six felony counts of
providing false personal financial statements to lenders to get
loans and financing for his real estate projects, and one count of
wire fraud in connection with a series of pension funds.
</P>
<P>
Symington's felony convictions required his ouster from office,
though he could have remained in office until he is sentenced on
November 10. Symington could face prison time and hefty fines.
</P>
