<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Nuclear Groups Call for Delay for Cassini Launch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Anti-nuclear activists and
some scientists, engineers and public health officials today urged
U.S. President Bill Clinton to delay the launch of NASA's
plutonium-powered Cassini probe to Saturn.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that the 33 kilograms of plutonium that
Cassini is to carry could pose a potentially lethal risk to humans
if the spacecraft blows up or re-enters Earth's atmosphere after
launch.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference with other Cassini opponents, physicist
Michio Kaku of the City University of New York said that NASA
estimated that Cassini plutonium leak could possibly lead to 2,300
cancers, but it did not take into account winds that could blow
radioactive plutonium over a wide area, increasing the cancer risk
for a much larger group of people.
</P>
<P>
Cassini is scheduled to blast off from Cape Canaveral October 6
but is likely to be delayed by a launch-pad slip-up that damaged
part of the spacecraft in August.
</P>
<P>
It was scheduled to fly by Venus twice, then fly by Earth and
Jupiter before arriving at Saturn in July 2004 for a four-year
study of the ringed planet.
</P>
<P>
The craft will be taken aloft by a Titan IV rocket, which NASA
acknowledged has a historical failure rate of one in 20. However,
NASA said the chances of a Titan IV launch accident releasing
plutonium were about one in 1,400.
</P>
<P>
The anti-nuclear group urged Clinton to postpone Cassini and to
authorize a new design for the mission so that it could use a new
solar power source developed by the European Space Agency.
</P>
<P>
Joining the Cassini opponents were also Alan Kohn, a retired
NASA official who handled emergency preparedness for staff at
Kennedy Space Center for two previous space missions carrying
plutonium power packs.
</P>
<P>
"Please help us to stop this criminal insanity, or else figure
out how we can provide permanent fallout shelters for all living
beings on the planet," Kohn said in a statement at the new
conference.
</P>
<P>
However, NASA said in a statement that the plutonium used to
power the craft is a heat-resistant ceramic form of plutonium
dioxide, which reduces the chance of it vaporizing either in a
fire or in the event it re-entered the Earth's atmosphere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
