<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Consumer Credit Increases 6.4 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Consumer debt outstanding
in the U.S. grew at a 6.4 percent annual rate to a seasonally
adjusted 1.225 trillion dollars in July, the U.S. Federal Reserve
(Fed) reported today.
</P>
<P>
That was the biggest advance since April and well above the
slow increases at rates of 0.8 percent in June and 2.7 percent in
May.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that American consumers resumed borrowing in
July, tapping their credit cards and securing auto loans after
taking a rest in the Spring and early Summer.
</P>
<P>
Much of the July credit advance came in the revolving loan
category, which is mostly credit cards. It rose at a 12.5 percent
annual rate to a seasonally adjusted 521.9 billion dollars, the
fastest pace in five months.
</P>
<P>
Auto loans outstanding were up at a 10.9 percent rate to 398.9
billion dollars after increasing at a 5.6 percent rate in June,
the speediest in three months.
</P>
<P>
However, other kinds of consumer debt shrank at a 9.7 percent
annual rate to 304.3 billion dollars after contracting at a 9.8
percent rate in June. This category includes loans for mobile
homes, education, boats and vacations.
</P>
<P>
The report doesn't include home mortgages or home equity loans.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the gain of consumer debt is a sign that
U.S. economy will accelerate in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
Economists also have nervously watched consumer credit levels
as increasing numbers of Americans -- more than a million a year
-- declare bankruptcy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
