<HEADLINE> U.S.,DPRK Officials to Hold Talks in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The State Department
announced on Monday that negotiators from the United States and
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) will meet on
Wednesday in Beijing to discuss the future of four-party peace
talks on the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley told reporters that
Deputy Assistant Secretary of State Charles Kartman, who will fly
to Beijing on Tuesday, will hold talks there with DPRK Vice
Foreign Minister Kim Gye-gwan.
</P>
<P>
Tension have risen between the United States and DPRK since
Washington announced to give asylum to defected DPRK Ambassador
Chang Sung-Gil and his brother Chang Sung-ho, also a diplomat,
last month.
</P>
<P>
Pyongyang has ever since suspended talks with Washington on
missile sales. And questions on possibility of the four-party
peace talks have also been raised because of the U.S. move of
granting the asylum.
</P>
<P>
Foley,however, said he saw "no indication of any change of
plans" on the DPRK part in relation to the four-party talks and
said Washington hopes Pyongyang will be present when the
four-party talks resume in a week or so.
</P>
<P>
The four-party talks include the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea, South Korea, the United States and China. The four
nations held the first preparatory session in New York last month
and agreed then to reconvene on September 15 to pursue a mutually
agreeable agenda for substantive negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
