<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Real Estate in Solid Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian commercial real
estate is in a solid recovery this year thanks to an improving
economy.
</P>
<P>
Across the country, vacancy rates are falling and rents are
rising, even in the long-suffering Toronto market, a report said
today.
</P>
<P>
Three factors are behind the resurrection -- a pickup in
economic activity that has increased demand for office, retail and
industrial space; a lack of new construction and low interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
"To say we're experiencing a boom now would be a big
stretch...What we are experiencing now is a very solid recovery,"
said a real estate analyst.
</P>
<P>
The vacancy rate in downtown Toronto was down to 11 percent at
midyear from 13 percent at the end of 1996 and 18 percent a few
years ago.
</P>
<P>
Vancouver's downtown vacancy rate is the country's lowest at
five percent, with Calgary next at 7.3 percent, according real
estate brokerage Royal Lepage Ltd.
</P>
<P>
"If the current idyllic conditions continue, then I see a
considerable additional upside," the analyst added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
