<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Summit Ends Keynoting Closer Ties for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLANTYRE (MALAWI), September 8 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) ended their one-day
summit meeting here today, with an eye for tighter ties among the
member countries for a final integration.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued at the end of the summit said that the
SADC summit has passed protocols in mining, education and
training, which called for joint efforts in tapping the huge
potential in the fields.
</P>
<P>
The development of the human resources was regarded by leaders
at the summit as a key for future development.
</P>
<P>
The summit discussed, among other issues, the gender equality
and the raising of the productivity in the region.
</P>
<P>
Gender equality is said by Nelson Mandela, SADC Chairman and
President of South Africa, as part of their efforts for full
democracy and development.
</P>
<P>
The sub-regional leaders agreed that they should ensure that
appropriate institutional mechanism is put in place to stir the
region for future prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the work to further consolidate their already
achieved democracy and good governance, as claimed by Bakili
Muluzi, President of Malawi, countries of the group need to
improve their science and technology.
</P>
<P>
The development of infrastructure and access to markets were
also urged as critical by the Malawian leader.
</P>
<P>
The group should join hands to put an end to being used as a
testing ground for economic or social experiment which originate
from rich but distant countries, Muluzi said at the summit.
</P>
<P>
SADC also needs "genuine outside partners", Muluzi said,
adding that members of the group should realize that the burden
of whatever they seek to achieve, falls squarely on their own
shoulders.
</P>
<P>
Economic success of SADC countries, the host country leader
said, depends on the meaningful cooperation and integration and
their total solidarity.
</P>
<P>
The summit also stressed political stability and peace in the
region and other parts of African continent.
</P>
<P>
SADC leaders said in the communique after the meeting that
security situation in the Great Lakes region, particularly in
Burundi, is still worrying, noting that efforts should be
encouraged to bring the military authorities to the political
negotiation in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The regional group which decided to take Congo (K) and
Seychelles as its new members to add to its 12 members at this
summit will hold its next summit in Mauritius next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
