<DOCNO> XIE19970909.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Drops Charges against Saudi Suspect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Justice Department
on Monday dropped criminal charges against a Saudi suspect who was
said to have been linked to the 1996 Khobar Tower truck bombing in
Saudi Arabia, killing 19 American servicemen.
</P>
<P>
Hani al-Sayegh, was brought to the United States from Canada
earlier this year under an agreement in which he would plead
guilty to lesser charges of plotting an aborted anti-American
attack in the Middle East, and help U.S. investigators make a
probe into the truck bombing.
</P>
<P>
In turn, he would not be extradited to Saudi Arabia, his home
country.
</P>
<P>
But al-Sayegh has not provide the requisite evidence, and the
Justice Department said "it is necessary that this prosecution be
withdrawn."The Justice Department said Saudi authorities have
advised the United States that they plan to seek al-Sayegh's
extradition in connection with the Khobar Towers truck bombing.
</P>
<P>
If Saudi autorities meet the requirements for extradition, then
"the United States would respond appropriatedly" to the request,
the Justice Department said, adding that it would pursue
immigration proceedings to remove al-Sayegh from the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
